2176  uint64_t ToSize = Context.getTypeSize(PromoteTypes[Idx]);
2177  if (FromSize < ToSize ||
2178  (FromSize == ToSize &&
2179  FromIsSigned == PromoteTypes[Idx]->isSignedIntegerType())) {
2180  // We found the type that we can promote to. If this is the
2181  // type we wanted, we have a promotion. Otherwise, no
2182  // promotion.
2183  return Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ToType, PromoteTypes[Idx]);
2184  }
2185  }
2186  }
2187 
2188  // An rvalue for an integral bit-field (9.6) can be converted to an
2189  // rvalue of type int if int can represent all the values of the
2190  // bit-field; otherwise, it can be converted to unsigned int if
2191  // unsigned int can represent all the values of the bit-field. If
2192  // the bit-field is larger yet, no integral promotion applies to
2193  // it. If the bit-field has an enumerated type, it is treated as any
2194  // other value of that type for promotion purposes (C++ 4.5p3).
2195  // FIXME: We should delay checking of bit-fields until we actually perform the
2196  // conversion.
2197  //
2198  // FIXME: In C, only bit-fields of types _Bool, int, or unsigned int may be
2199  // promoted, per C11 6.3.1.1/2. We promote all bit-fields (including enum
2200  // bit-fields and those whose underlying type is larger than int) for GCC
2201  // compatibility.
2202  if (From) {
2203  if (FieldDecl *MemberDecl = From->getSourceBitField()) {
2204  Optional<llvm::APSInt> BitWidth;
2205  if (FromType->isIntegralType(Context) &&
2206  (BitWidth =
2207  MemberDecl->getBitWidth()->getIntegerConstantExpr(Context))) {
2208  llvm::APSInt ToSize(BitWidth->getBitWidth(), BitWidth->isUnsigned());
2209  ToSize = Context.getTypeSize(ToType);
2210 
2211  // Are we promoting to an int from a bitfield that fits in an int?
2212  if (*BitWidth < ToSize ||
2213  (FromType->isSignedIntegerType() && *BitWidth <= ToSize)) {
2214  return To->getKind() == BuiltinType::Int;
2215  }
2216 
2217  // Are we promoting to an unsigned int from an unsigned bitfield
2218  // that fits into an unsigned int?
2219  if (FromType->isUnsignedIntegerType() && *BitWidth <= ToSize) {
2220  return To->getKind() == BuiltinType::UInt;
2221  }
2222 
2223  return false;
2224  }
2225  }
2226  }
2227 
2228  // An rvalue of type bool can be converted to an rvalue of type int,
2229  // with false becoming zero and true becoming one (C++ 4.5p4).
2230  if (FromType->isBooleanType() && To->getKind() == BuiltinType::Int) {
2231  return true;
2232  }
2233 
2234  return false;
2235 }
2236 
2237 /// IsFloatingPointPromotion - Determines whether the conversion from
2238 /// FromType to ToType is a floating point promotion (C++ 4.6). If so,
2239 /// returns true and sets PromotedType to the promoted type.
2240 bool Sema::IsFloatingPointPromotion(QualType FromType, QualType ToType) {
2241  if (const BuiltinType *FromBuiltin = FromType->getAs<BuiltinType>())
2242  if (const BuiltinType *ToBuiltin = ToType->getAs<BuiltinType>()) {
2243  /// An rvalue of type float can be converted to an rvalue of type
2244  /// double. (C++ 4.6p1).
2245  if (FromBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Float &&
2246  ToBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Double)
2247  return true;
2248 
2249  // C99 6.3.1.5p1:
2250  // When a float is promoted to double or long double, or a
2251  // double is promoted to long double [...].
2252  if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus &&
2253  (FromBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Float ||
2254  FromBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Double) &&
2255  (ToBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::LongDouble ||
2256  ToBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Float128 ||
2257  ToBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Ibm128))
2258  return true;
2259 
2260  // Half can be promoted to float.
2261  if (!getLangOpts().NativeHalfType &&
2262  FromBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Half &&
2263  ToBuiltin->getKind() == BuiltinType::Float)
2264  return true;
2265  }
2266 
2267  return false;
2268 }
2269 
2270 /// Determine if a conversion is a complex promotion.
2271 ///
2272 /// A complex promotion is defined as a complex -> complex conversion
2273 /// where the conversion between the underlying real types is a
2274 /// floating-point or integral promotion.
2275 bool Sema::IsComplexPromotion(QualType FromType, QualType ToType) {
2276  const ComplexType *FromComplex = FromType->getAs<ComplexType>();
2277  if (!FromComplex)
2278  return false;
2279 
2280  const ComplexType *ToComplex = ToType->getAs<ComplexType>();
2281  if (!ToComplex)
2282  return false;
2283 
2284  return IsFloatingPointPromotion(FromComplex->getElementType(),
2285  ToComplex->getElementType()) ||
2286  IsIntegralPromotion(nullptr, FromComplex->getElementType(),
2287  ToComplex->getElementType());
2288 }
2289 
2290 /// BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType - In a pointer conversion from
2291 /// the pointer type FromPtr to a pointer to type ToPointee, with the
2292 /// same type qualifiers as FromPtr has on its pointee type. ToType,
2293 /// if non-empty, will be a pointer to ToType that may or may not have
2294 /// the right set of qualifiers on its pointee.
2295 ///
2296 static QualType
2297 BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(const Type *FromPtr,
2298  QualType ToPointee, QualType ToType,
2299  ASTContext &Context,
2300  bool StripObjCLifetime = false) {
2301  assert((FromPtr->getTypeClass() == Type::Pointer ||
2302  FromPtr->getTypeClass() == Type::ObjCObjectPointer) &&
2303  "Invalid similarly-qualified pointer type");
2304 
2305  /// Conversions to 'id' subsume cv-qualifier conversions.
2306  if (ToType->isObjCIdType() || ToType->isObjCQualifiedIdType())
2307  return ToType.getUnqualifiedType();
2308 
2309  QualType CanonFromPointee
2310  = Context.getCanonicalType(FromPtr->getPointeeType());
2311  QualType CanonToPointee = Context.getCanonicalType(ToPointee);
2312  Qualifiers Quals = CanonFromPointee.getQualifiers();
2313 
2314  if (StripObjCLifetime)
2315  Quals.removeObjCLifetime();
2316 
2317  // Exact qualifier match -> return the pointer type we're converting to.
2318  if (CanonToPointee.getLocalQualifiers() == Quals) {
2319  // ToType is exactly what we need. Return it.
2320  if (!ToType.isNull())
2321  return ToType.getUnqualifiedType();
2322 
2323  // Build a pointer to ToPointee. It has the right qualifiers
2324  // already.
2325  if (isa<ObjCObjectPointerType>(ToType))
2326  return Context.getObjCObjectPointerType(ToPointee);
2327  return Context.getPointerType(ToPointee);
2328  }
2329 
2330  // Just build a canonical type that has the right qualifiers.
2331  QualType QualifiedCanonToPointee
2332  = Context.getQualifiedType(CanonToPointee.getLocalUnqualifiedType(), Quals);
2333 
2334  if (isa<ObjCObjectPointerType>(ToType))
2335  return Context.getObjCObjectPointerType(QualifiedCanonToPointee);
2336  return Context.getPointerType(QualifiedCanonToPointee);
2337 }
2338 
2339 static bool isNullPointerConstantForConversion(Expr *Expr,
2340  bool InOverloadResolution,
2341  ASTContext &Context) {
2342  // Handle value-dependent integral null pointer constants correctly.
2343  // http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/cwg_active.html#903
2344  if (Expr->isValueDependent() && !Expr->isTypeDependent() &&
2345  Expr->getType()->isIntegerType() && !Expr->getType()->isEnumeralType())
2346  return !InOverloadResolution;
2347 
2348  return Expr->isNullPointerConstant(Context,
2349  InOverloadResolution? Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNotNull
2350  : Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNull);
2351 }
2352 
2353 /// IsPointerConversion - Determines whether the conversion of the
2354 /// expression From, which has the (possibly adjusted) type FromType,
2355 /// can be converted to the type ToType via a pointer conversion (C++
2356 /// 4.10). If so, returns true and places the converted type (that
2357 /// might differ from ToType in its cv-qualifiers at some level) into
2358 /// ConvertedType.
2359 ///
2360 /// This routine also supports conversions to and from block pointers
2361 /// and conversions with Objective-C's 'id', 'id<protocols...>', and
2362 /// pointers to interfaces. FIXME: Once we've determined the
2363 /// appropriate overloading rules for Objective-C, we may want to
2364 /// split the Objective-C checks into a different routine; however,
2365 /// GCC seems to consider all of these conversions to be pointer
2366 /// conversions, so for now they live here. IncompatibleObjC will be
2367 /// set if the conversion is an allowed Objective-C conversion that
2368 /// should result in a warning.
2369 bool Sema::IsPointerConversion(Expr *From, QualType FromType, QualType ToType,
2370  bool InOverloadResolution,
2371  QualType& ConvertedType,
2372  bool &IncompatibleObjC) {
2373  IncompatibleObjC = false;
2374  if (isObjCPointerConversion(FromType, ToType, ConvertedType,
2375  IncompatibleObjC))
2376  return true;
2377 
2378  // Conversion from a null pointer constant to any Objective-C pointer type.
2379  if (ToType->isObjCObjectPointerType() &&
2380  isNullPointerConstantForConversion(From, InOverloadResolution, Context)) {
2381  ConvertedType = ToType;
2382  return true;
2383  }
2384 
2385  // Blocks: Block pointers can be converted to void*.
2386  if (FromType->isBlockPointerType() && ToType->isPointerType() &&
2387  ToType->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType()->isVoidType()) {
2388  ConvertedType = ToType;
2389  return true;
2390  }
2391  // Blocks: A null pointer constant can be converted to a block
2392  // pointer type.
2393  if (ToType->isBlockPointerType() &&
2394  isNullPointerConstantForConversion(From, InOverloadResolution, Context)) {
2395  ConvertedType = ToType;
2396  return true;
2397  }
2398 
2399  // If the left-hand-side is nullptr_t, the right side can be a null
2400  // pointer constant.
2401  if (ToType->isNullPtrType() &&
2402  isNullPointerConstantForConversion(From, InOverloadResolution, Context)) {
2403  ConvertedType = ToType;
2404  return true;
2405  }
2406 
2407  const PointerType* ToTypePtr = ToType->getAs<PointerType>();
2408  if (!ToTypePtr)
2409  return false;
2410 
2411  // A null pointer constant can be converted to a pointer type (C++ 4.10p1).
2412  if (isNullPointerConstantForConversion(From, InOverloadResolution, Context)) {
2413  ConvertedType = ToType;
2414  return true;
2415  }
2416 
2417  // Beyond this point, both types need to be pointers
2418  // , including objective-c pointers.
2419  QualType ToPointeeType = ToTypePtr->getPointeeType();
2420  if (FromType->isObjCObjectPointerType() && ToPointeeType->isVoidType() &&
2421  !getLangOpts().ObjCAutoRefCount) {
2422  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(
2423  FromType->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>(), ToPointeeType, ToType,
2424  Context);
2425  return true;
2426  }
2427  const PointerType *FromTypePtr = FromType->getAs<PointerType>();
2428  if (!FromTypePtr)
2429  return false;
2430 
2431  QualType FromPointeeType = FromTypePtr->getPointeeType();
2432 
2433  // If the unqualified pointee types are the same, this can't be a
2434  // pointer conversion, so don't do all of the work below.
2435  if (Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType))
2436  return false;
2437 
2438  // An rvalue of type "pointer to cv T," where T is an object type,
2439  // can be converted to an rvalue of type "pointer to cv void" (C++
2440  // 4.10p2).
2441  if (FromPointeeType->isIncompleteOrObjectType() &&
2442  ToPointeeType->isVoidType()) {
2443  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromTypePtr,
2444  ToPointeeType,
2445  ToType, Context,
2446  /*StripObjCLifetime=*/true);
2447  return true;
2448  }
2449 
2450  // MSVC allows implicit function to void* type conversion.
2451  if (getLangOpts().MSVCCompat && FromPointeeType->isFunctionType() &&
2452  ToPointeeType->isVoidType()) {
2453  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromTypePtr,
2454  ToPointeeType,
2455  ToType, Context);
2456  return true;
2457  }
2458 
2459  // When we're overloading in C, we allow a special kind of pointer
2460  // conversion for compatible-but-not-identical pointee types.
2461  if (!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus &&
2462  Context.typesAreCompatible(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType)) {
2463  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromTypePtr,
2464  ToPointeeType,
2465  ToType, Context);
2466  return true;
2467  }
2468 
2469  // C++ [conv.ptr]p3:
2470  //
2471  // An rvalue of type "pointer to cv D," where D is a class type,
2472  // can be converted to an rvalue of type "pointer to cv B," where
2473  // B is a base class (clause 10) of D. If B is an inaccessible
2474  // (clause 11) or ambiguous (10.2) base class of D, a program that
2475  // necessitates this conversion is ill-formed. The result of the
2476  // conversion is a pointer to the base class sub-object of the
2477  // derived class object. The null pointer value is converted to
2478  // the null pointer value of the destination type.
2479  //
2480  // Note that we do not check for ambiguity or inaccessibility
2481  // here. That is handled by CheckPointerConversion.
2482  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && FromPointeeType->isRecordType() &&
2483  ToPointeeType->isRecordType() &&
2484  !Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType) &&
2485  IsDerivedFrom(From->getBeginLoc(), FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType)) {
2486  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromTypePtr,
2487  ToPointeeType,
2488  ToType, Context);
2489  return true;
2490  }
2491 
2492  if (FromPointeeType->isVectorType() && ToPointeeType->isVectorType() &&
2493  Context.areCompatibleVectorTypes(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType)) {
2494  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromTypePtr,
2495  ToPointeeType,
2496  ToType, Context);
2497  return true;
2498  }
2499 
2500  return false;
2501 }
2502 
2503 /// Adopt the given qualifiers for the given type.
2504 static QualType AdoptQualifiers(ASTContext &Context, QualType T, Qualifiers Qs){
2505  Qualifiers TQs = T.getQualifiers();
2506 
2507  // Check whether qualifiers already match.
2508  if (TQs == Qs)
2509  return T;
2510 
2511  if (Qs.compatiblyIncludes(TQs))
2512  return Context.getQualifiedType(T, Qs);
2513 
2514  return Context.getQualifiedType(T.getUnqualifiedType(), Qs);
2515 }
2516 
2517 /// isObjCPointerConversion - Determines whether this is an
2518 /// Objective-C pointer conversion. Subroutine of IsPointerConversion,
2519 /// with the same arguments and return values.
2520 bool Sema::isObjCPointerConversion(QualType FromType, QualType ToType,
2521  QualType& ConvertedType,
2522  bool &IncompatibleObjC) {
2523  if (!getLangOpts().ObjC)
2524  return false;
2525 
2526  // The set of qualifiers on the type we're converting from.
2527  Qualifiers FromQualifiers = FromType.getQualifiers();
2528 
2529  // First, we handle all conversions on ObjC object pointer types.
2530  const ObjCObjectPointerType* ToObjCPtr =
2531  ToType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
2532  const ObjCObjectPointerType *FromObjCPtr =
2533  FromType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
2534 
2535  if (ToObjCPtr && FromObjCPtr) {
2536  // If the pointee types are the same (ignoring qualifications),
2537  // then this is not a pointer conversion.
2538  if (Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ToObjCPtr->getPointeeType(),
2539  FromObjCPtr->getPointeeType()))
2540  return false;
2541 
2542  // Conversion between Objective-C pointers.
2543  if (Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(ToObjCPtr, FromObjCPtr)) {
2544  const ObjCInterfaceType* LHS = ToObjCPtr->getInterfaceType();
2545  const ObjCInterfaceType* RHS = FromObjCPtr->getInterfaceType();
2546  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus && LHS && RHS &&
2547  !ToObjCPtr->getPointeeType().isAtLeastAsQualifiedAs(
2548  FromObjCPtr->getPointeeType()))
2549  return false;
2550  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromObjCPtr,
2551  ToObjCPtr->getPointeeType(),
2552  ToType, Context);
2553  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ConvertedType, FromQualifiers);
2554  return true;
2555  }
2556 
2557  if (Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(FromObjCPtr, ToObjCPtr)) {
2558  // Okay: this is some kind of implicit downcast of Objective-C
2559  // interfaces, which is permitted. However, we're going to
2560  // complain about it.
2561  IncompatibleObjC = true;
2562  ConvertedType = BuildSimilarlyQualifiedPointerType(FromObjCPtr,
2563  ToObjCPtr->getPointeeType(),
2564  ToType, Context);
2565  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ConvertedType, FromQualifiers);
2566  return true;
2567  }
2568  }
2569  // Beyond this point, both types need to be C pointers or block pointers.
2570  QualType ToPointeeType;
2571  if (const PointerType *ToCPtr = ToType->getAs<PointerType>())
2572  ToPointeeType = ToCPtr->getPointeeType();
2573  else if (const BlockPointerType *ToBlockPtr =
2574  ToType->getAs<BlockPointerType>()) {
2575  // Objective C++: We're able to convert from a pointer to any object
2576  // to a block pointer type.
2577  if (FromObjCPtr && FromObjCPtr->isObjCBuiltinType()) {
2578  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ToType, FromQualifiers);
2579  return true;
2580  }
2581  ToPointeeType = ToBlockPtr->getPointeeType();
2582  }
2583  else if (FromType->getAs<BlockPointerType>() &&
2584  ToObjCPtr && ToObjCPtr->isObjCBuiltinType()) {
2585  // Objective C++: We're able to convert from a block pointer type to a
2586  // pointer to any object.
2587  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ToType, FromQualifiers);
2588  return true;
2589  }
2590  else
2591  return false;
2592 
2593  QualType FromPointeeType;
2594  if (const PointerType *FromCPtr = FromType->getAs<PointerType>())
2595  FromPointeeType = FromCPtr->getPointeeType();
2596  else if (const BlockPointerType *FromBlockPtr =
2597  FromType->getAs<BlockPointerType>())
2598  FromPointeeType = FromBlockPtr->getPointeeType();
2599  else
2600  return false;
2601 
2602  // If we have pointers to pointers, recursively check whether this
2603  // is an Objective-C conversion.
2604  if (FromPointeeType->isPointerType() && ToPointeeType->isPointerType() &&
2605  isObjCPointerConversion(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType, ConvertedType,
2606  IncompatibleObjC)) {
2607  // We always complain about this conversion.
2608  IncompatibleObjC = true;
2609  ConvertedType = Context.getPointerType(ConvertedType);
2610  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ConvertedType, FromQualifiers);
2611  return true;
2612  }
2613  // Allow conversion of pointee being objective-c pointer to another one;
2614  // as in I* to id.
2615  if (FromPointeeType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>() &&
2616  ToPointeeType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>() &&
2617  isObjCPointerConversion(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType, ConvertedType,
2618  IncompatibleObjC)) {
2619 
2620  ConvertedType = Context.getPointerType(ConvertedType);
2621  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ConvertedType, FromQualifiers);
2622  return true;
2623  }
2624 
2625  // If we have pointers to functions or blocks, check whether the only
2626  // differences in the argument and result types are in Objective-C
2627  // pointer conversions. If so, we permit the conversion (but
2628  // complain about it).
2629  const FunctionProtoType *FromFunctionType
2630  = FromPointeeType->getAs<FunctionProtoType>();
2631  const FunctionProtoType *ToFunctionType
2632  = ToPointeeType->getAs<FunctionProtoType>();
2633  if (FromFunctionType && ToFunctionType) {
2634  // If the function types are exactly the same, this isn't an
2635  // Objective-C pointer conversion.
2636  if (Context.getCanonicalType(FromPointeeType)
2637  == Context.getCanonicalType(ToPointeeType))
2638  return false;
2639 
2640  // Perform the quick checks that will tell us whether these
2641  // function types are obviously different.
2642  if (FromFunctionType->getNumParams() != ToFunctionType->getNumParams() ||
2643  FromFunctionType->isVariadic() != ToFunctionType->isVariadic() ||
2644  FromFunctionType->getMethodQuals() != ToFunctionType->getMethodQuals())
2645  return false;
2646 
2647  bool HasObjCConversion = false;
2648  if (Context.getCanonicalType(FromFunctionType->getReturnType()) ==
2649  Context.getCanonicalType(ToFunctionType->getReturnType())) {
2650  // Okay, the types match exactly. Nothing to do.
2651  } else if (isObjCPointerConversion(FromFunctionType->getReturnType(),
2652  ToFunctionType->getReturnType(),
2653  ConvertedType, IncompatibleObjC)) {
2654  // Okay, we have an Objective-C pointer conversion.
2655  HasObjCConversion = true;
2656  } else {
2657  // Function types are too different. Abort.
2658  return false;
2659  }
2660 
2661  // Check argument types.
2662  for (unsigned ArgIdx = 0, NumArgs = FromFunctionType->getNumParams();
2663  ArgIdx != NumArgs; ++ArgIdx) {
2664  QualType FromArgType = FromFunctionType->getParamType(ArgIdx);
2665  QualType ToArgType = ToFunctionType->getParamType(ArgIdx);
2666  if (Context.getCanonicalType(FromArgType)
2667  == Context.getCanonicalType(ToArgType)) {
2668  // Okay, the types match exactly. Nothing to do.
2669  } else if (isObjCPointerConversion(FromArgType, ToArgType,
2670  ConvertedType, IncompatibleObjC)) {
2671  // Okay, we have an Objective-C pointer conversion.
2672  HasObjCConversion = true;
2673  } else {
2674  // Argument types are too different. Abort.
2675  return false;
2676  }
2677  }
2678 
2679  if (HasObjCConversion) {
2680  // We had an Objective-C conversion. Allow this pointer
2681  // conversion, but complain about it.
2682  ConvertedType = AdoptQualifiers(Context, ToType, FromQualifiers);
2683  IncompatibleObjC = true;
2684  return true;
2685  }
2686  }
2687 
2688  return false;
2689 }
2690 
2691 /// Determine whether this is an Objective-C writeback conversion,
2692 /// used for parameter passing when performing automatic reference counting.
2693 ///
2694 /// \param FromType The type we're converting form.
2695 ///
2696 /// \param ToType The type we're converting to.
2697 ///
2698 /// \param ConvertedType The type that will be produced after applying
2699 /// this conversion.
2700 bool Sema::isObjCWritebackConversion(QualType FromType, QualType ToType,
2701  QualType &ConvertedType) {
2702  if (!getLangOpts().ObjCAutoRefCount ||
2703  Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromType, ToType))
2704  return false;
2705 
2706  // Parameter must be a pointer to __autoreleasing (with no other qualifiers).
2707  QualType ToPointee;
2708  if (const PointerType *ToPointer = ToType->getAs<PointerType>())
2709  ToPointee = ToPointer->getPointeeType();
2710  else
2711  return false;
2712 
2713  Qualifiers ToQuals = ToPointee.getQualifiers();
2714  if (!ToPointee->isObjCLifetimeType() ||
2715  ToQuals.getObjCLifetime() != Qualifiers::OCL_Autoreleasing ||
2716  !ToQuals.withoutObjCLifetime().empty())
2717  return false;
2718 
2719  // Argument must be a pointer to __strong to __weak.
2720  QualType FromPointee;
2721  if (const PointerType *FromPointer = FromType->getAs<PointerType>())
2722  FromPointee = FromPointer->getPointeeType();
2723  else
2724  return false;
2725 
2726  Qualifiers FromQuals = FromPointee.getQualifiers();
2727  if (!FromPointee->isObjCLifetimeType() ||
2728  (FromQuals.getObjCLifetime() != Qualifiers::OCL_Strong &&
2729  FromQuals.getObjCLifetime() != Qualifiers::OCL_Weak))
2730  return false;
2731 
2732  // Make sure that we have compatible qualifiers.
2733  FromQuals.setObjCLifetime(Qualifiers::OCL_Autoreleasing);
2734  if (!ToQuals.compatiblyIncludes(FromQuals))
2735  return false;
2736 
2737  // Remove qualifiers from the pointee type we're converting from; they
2738  // aren't used in the compatibility check belong, and we'll be adding back
2739  // qualifiers (with __autoreleasing) if the compatibility check succeeds.
2740  FromPointee = FromPointee.getUnqualifiedType();
2741 
2742  // The unqualified form of the pointee types must be compatible.
2743  ToPointee = ToPointee.getUnqualifiedType();
2744  bool IncompatibleObjC;
2745  if (Context.typesAreCompatible(FromPointee, ToPointee))
2746  FromPointee = ToPointee;
2747  else if (!isObjCPointerConversion(FromPointee, ToPointee, FromPointee,
2748  IncompatibleObjC))
2749  return false;
2750 
2751  /// Construct the type we're converting to, which is a pointer to
2752  /// __autoreleasing pointee.
2753  FromPointee = Context.getQualifiedType(FromPointee, FromQuals);
2754  ConvertedType = Context.getPointerType(FromPointee);
2755  return true;
2756 }
2757 
2758 bool Sema::IsBlockPointerConversion(QualType FromType, QualType ToType,
2759  QualType& ConvertedType) {
2760  QualType ToPointeeType;
2761  if (const BlockPointerType *ToBlockPtr =
2762  ToType->getAs<BlockPointerType>())
2763  ToPointeeType = ToBlockPtr->getPointeeType();
2764  else
2765  return false;
2766 
2767  QualType FromPointeeType;
2768  if (const BlockPointerType *FromBlockPtr =
2769  FromType->getAs<BlockPointerType>())
2770  FromPointeeType = FromBlockPtr->getPointeeType();
2771  else
2772  return false;
2773  // We have pointer to blocks, check whether the only
2774  // differences in the argument and result types are in Objective-C
2775  // pointer conversions. If so, we permit the conversion.
2776 
2777  const FunctionProtoType *FromFunctionType
2778  = FromPointeeType->getAs<FunctionProtoType>();
2779  const FunctionProtoType *ToFunctionType
2780  = ToPointeeType->getAs<FunctionProtoType>();
2781 
2782  if (!FromFunctionType || !ToFunctionType)
2783  return false;
2784 
2785  if (Context.hasSameType(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType))
2786  return true;
2787 
2788  // Perform the quick checks that will tell us whether these
2789  // function types are obviously different.
2790  if (FromFunctionType->getNumParams() != ToFunctionType->getNumParams() ||
2791  FromFunctionType->isVariadic() != ToFunctionType->isVariadic())
2792  return false;
2793 
2794  FunctionType::ExtInfo FromEInfo = FromFunctionType->getExtInfo();
2795  FunctionType::ExtInfo ToEInfo = ToFunctionType->getExtInfo();
2796  if (FromEInfo != ToEInfo)
2797  return false;
2798 
2799  bool IncompatibleObjC = false;
2800  if (Context.hasSameType(FromFunctionType->getReturnType(),
2801  ToFunctionType->getReturnType())) {
2802  // Okay, the types match exactly. Nothing to do.
2803  } else {
2804  QualType RHS = FromFunctionType->getReturnType();
2805  QualType LHS = ToFunctionType->getReturnType();
2806  if ((!getLangOpts().CPlusPlus || !RHS->isRecordType()) &&
2807  !RHS.hasQualifiers() && LHS.hasQualifiers())
2808  LHS = LHS.getUnqualifiedType();
2809 
2810  if (Context.hasSameType(RHS,LHS)) {
2811  // OK exact match.
2812  } else if (isObjCPointerConversion(RHS, LHS,
2813  ConvertedType, IncompatibleObjC)) {
2814  if (IncompatibleObjC)
2815  return false;
2816  // Okay, we have an Objective-C pointer conversion.
2817  }
2818  else
2819  return false;
2820  }
2821 
2822  // Check argument types.
2823  for (unsigned ArgIdx = 0, NumArgs = FromFunctionType->getNumParams();
2824  ArgIdx != NumArgs; ++ArgIdx) {
2825  IncompatibleObjC = false;
2826  QualType FromArgType = FromFunctionType->getParamType(ArgIdx);
2827  QualType ToArgType = ToFunctionType->getParamType(ArgIdx);
2828  if (Context.hasSameType(FromArgType, ToArgType)) {
2829  // Okay, the types match exactly. Nothing to do.
2830  } else if (isObjCPointerConversion(ToArgType, FromArgType,
2831  ConvertedType, IncompatibleObjC)) {
2832  if (IncompatibleObjC)
2833  return false;
2834  // Okay, we have an Objective-C pointer conversion.
2835  } else
2836  // Argument types are too different. Abort.
2837  return false;
2838  }
2839 
2840  SmallVector<FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo, 4> NewParamInfos;
2841  bool CanUseToFPT, CanUseFromFPT;
2842  if (!Context.mergeExtParameterInfo(ToFunctionType, FromFunctionType,
2843  CanUseToFPT, CanUseFromFPT,
2844  NewParamInfos))
2845  return false;
2846 
2847  ConvertedType = ToType;
2848  return true;
2849 }

2851 enum {
2852  ft_default,
2853  ft_different_class,
2854  ft_parameter_arity,
2855  ft_parameter_mismatch,
2856  ft_return_type,
2857  ft_qualifer_mismatch,
2858  ft_noexcept
2859 };

2861 /// Attempts to get the FunctionProtoType from a Type. Handles
2862 /// MemberFunctionPointers properly.
2863 static const FunctionProtoType *tryGetFunctionProtoType(QualType FromType) {
2864  if (auto *FPT = FromType->getAs<FunctionProtoType>())
2865  return FPT;
2866 
2867  if (auto *MPT = FromType->getAs<MemberPointerType>())
2868  return MPT->getPointeeType()->getAs<FunctionProtoType>();
2869 
2870  return nullptr;
2871 }
2872 
2873 /// HandleFunctionTypeMismatch - Gives diagnostic information for differeing
2874 /// function types. Catches different number of parameter, mismatch in
2875 /// parameter types, and different return types.
2876 void Sema::HandleFunctionTypeMismatch(PartialDiagnostic &PDiag,
2877  QualType FromType, QualType ToType) {
2878  // If either type is not valid, include no extra info.
2879  if (FromType.isNull() || ToType.isNull()) {
2880  PDiag << ft_default;
2881  return;
2882  }
2883 
2884  // Get the function type from the pointers.
2885  if (FromType->isMemberPointerType() && ToType->isMemberPointerType()) {
2886  const auto *FromMember = FromType->castAs<MemberPointerType>(),
2887  *ToMember = ToType->castAs<MemberPointerType>();
2888  if (!Context.hasSameType(FromMember->getClass(), ToMember->getClass())) {
2889  PDiag << ft_different_class << QualType(ToMember->getClass(), 0)
2890  << QualType(FromMember->getClass(), 0);
2891  return;
2892  }
2893  FromType = FromMember->getPointeeType();
2894  ToType = ToMember->getPointeeType();
2895  }
2896 
2897  if (FromType->isPointerType())
2898  FromType = FromType->getPointeeType();
2899  if (ToType->isPointerType())
2900  ToType = ToType->getPointeeType();
2901 
2902  // Remove references.
2903  FromType = FromType.getNonReferenceType();
2904  ToType = ToType.getNonReferenceType();
2905 
2906  // Don't print extra info for non-specialized template functions.
2907  if (FromType->isInstantiationDependentType() &&
2908  !FromType->getAs<TemplateSpecializationType>()) {
2909  PDiag << ft_default;
2910  return;
2911  }
2912 
2913  // No extra info for same types.
2914  if (Context.hasSameType(FromType, ToType)) {
2915  PDiag << ft_default;
2916  return;
2917  }
2918 
2919  const FunctionProtoType *FromFunction = tryGetFunctionProtoType(FromType),
2920  *ToFunction = tryGetFunctionProtoType(ToType);
2921 
2922  // Both types need to be function types.
2923  if (!FromFunction || !ToFunction) {
2924  PDiag << ft_default;
2925  return;
2926  }
2927 
2928  if (FromFunction->getNumParams() != ToFunction->getNumParams()) {
2929  PDiag << ft_parameter_arity << ToFunction->getNumParams()
2930  << FromFunction->getNumParams();
2931  return;
2932  }
2933 
2934  // Handle different parameter types.
2935  unsigned ArgPos;
2936  if (!FunctionParamTypesAreEqual(FromFunction, ToFunction, &ArgPos)) {
2937  PDiag << ft_parameter_mismatch << ArgPos + 1
2938  << ToFunction->getParamType(ArgPos)
2939  << FromFunction->getParamType(ArgPos);
2940  return;
2941  }
2942 
2943  // Handle different return type.
2944  if (!Context.hasSameType(FromFunction->getReturnType(),
2945  ToFunction->getReturnType())) {
2946  PDiag << ft_return_type << ToFunction->getReturnType()
2947  << FromFunction->getReturnType();
2948  return;
2949  }
2950 
2951  if (FromFunction->getMethodQuals() != ToFunction->getMethodQuals()) {
2952  PDiag << ft_qualifer_mismatch << ToFunction->getMethodQuals()
2953  << FromFunction->getMethodQuals();
2954  return;
2955  }
2956 
2957  // Handle exception specification differences on canonical type (in C++17
2958  // onwards).
2959  if (cast<FunctionProtoType>(FromFunction->getCanonicalTypeUnqualified())
2960  ->isNothrow() !=
2961  cast<FunctionProtoType>(ToFunction->getCanonicalTypeUnqualified())
2962  ->isNothrow()) {
2963  PDiag << ft_noexcept;
2964  return;
2965  }
2966 
2967  // Unable to find a difference, so add no extra info.
2968  PDiag << ft_default;
2969 }
2970 
2971 /// FunctionParamTypesAreEqual - This routine checks two function proto types
2972 /// for equality of their argument types. Caller has already checked that
2973 /// they have same number of arguments. If the parameters are different,
2974 /// ArgPos will have the parameter index of the first different parameter.
2975 bool Sema::FunctionParamTypesAreEqual(const FunctionProtoType *OldType,
2976  const FunctionProtoType *NewType,
2977  unsigned *ArgPos) {
2978  for (FunctionProtoType::param_type_iterator O = OldType->param_type_begin(),
2979  N = NewType->param_type_begin(),
2980  E = OldType->param_type_end();
2981  O && (O != E); ++O, ++N) {
2982  // Ignore address spaces in pointee type. This is to disallow overloading
2983  // on __ptr32/__ptr64 address spaces.
2984  QualType Old = Context.removePtrSizeAddrSpace(O->getUnqualifiedType());
2985  QualType New = Context.removePtrSizeAddrSpace(N->getUnqualifiedType());
2986 
2987  if (!Context.hasSameType(Old, New)) {
2988  if (ArgPos)
2989  *ArgPos = O - OldType->param_type_begin();
2990  return false;
2991  }
2992  }
2993  return true;
2994 }

2996 /// CheckPointerConversion - Check the pointer conversion from the
2997 /// expression From to the type ToType. This routine checks for
2998 /// ambiguous or inaccessible derived-to-base pointer
2999 /// conversions for which IsPointerConversion has already returned
3000 /// true. It returns true and produces a diagnostic if there was an
3001 /// error, or returns false otherwise.
3002 bool Sema::CheckPointerConversion(Expr *From, QualType ToType,
3003  CastKind &Kind,
3004  CXXCastPath& BasePath,
3005  bool IgnoreBaseAccess,
3006  bool Diagnose) {
3007  QualType FromType = From->getType();
3008  bool IsCStyleOrFunctionalCast = IgnoreBaseAccess;
3009 
3010  Kind = CK_BitCast;
3011 
3012  if (Diagnose && !IsCStyleOrFunctionalCast && !FromType->isAnyPointerType() &&
3013  From->isNullPointerConstant(Context, Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNotNull) ==
3014  Expr::NPCK_ZeroExpression) {
3015  if (Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(From->getType(), Context.BoolTy))
3016  DiagRuntimeBehavior(From->getExprLoc(), From,
3017  PDiag(diag::warn_impcast_bool_to_null_pointer)
3018  << ToType << From->getSourceRange());
3019  else if (!isUnevaluatedContext())
3020  Diag(From->getExprLoc(), diag::warn_non_literal_null_pointer)
3021  << ToType << From->getSourceRange();
3022  }
3023  if (const PointerType *ToPtrType = ToType->getAs<PointerType>()) {
3024  if (const PointerType *FromPtrType = FromType->getAs<PointerType>()) {
3025  QualType FromPointeeType = FromPtrType->getPointeeType(),
3026  ToPointeeType = ToPtrType->getPointeeType();
3027 
3028  if (FromPointeeType->isRecordType() && ToPointeeType->isRecordType() &&
3029  !Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType)) {
3030  // We must have a derived-to-base conversion. Check an
3031  // ambiguous or inaccessible conversion.
3032  unsigned InaccessibleID = 0;
3033  unsigned AmbiguousID = 0;
3034  if (Diagnose) {
3035  InaccessibleID = diag::err_upcast_to_inaccessible_base;
3036  AmbiguousID = diag::err_ambiguous_derived_to_base_conv;
3037  }
3038  if (CheckDerivedToBaseConversion(
3039  FromPointeeType, ToPointeeType, InaccessibleID, AmbiguousID,
3040  From->getExprLoc(), From->getSourceRange(), DeclarationName(),
3041  &BasePath, IgnoreBaseAccess))
3042  return true;
3043 
3044  // The conversion was successful.
3045  Kind = CK_DerivedToBase;
3046  }
3047 
3048  if (Diagnose && !IsCStyleOrFunctionalCast &&
3049  FromPointeeType->isFunctionType() && ToPointeeType->isVoidType()) {
3050  assert(getLangOpts().MSVCCompat &&
3051  "this should only be possible with MSVCCompat!");
3052  Diag(From->getExprLoc(), diag::ext_ms_impcast_fn_obj)
3053  << From->getSourceRange();
3054  }
3055  }
3056  } else if (const ObjCObjectPointerType *ToPtrType =
3057  ToType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>()) {
3058  if (const ObjCObjectPointerType *FromPtrType =
3059  FromType->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>()) {
3060  // Objective-C++ conversions are always okay.
3061  // FIXME: We should have a different class of conversions for the
3062  // Objective-C++ implicit conversions.
3063  if (FromPtrType->isObjCBuiltinType() || ToPtrType->isObjCBuiltinType())
3064  return false;
3065  } else if (FromType->isBlockPointerType()) {
3066  Kind = CK_BlockPointerToObjCPointerCast;
3067  } else {
3068  Kind = CK_CPointerToObjCPointerCast;
3069  }
3070  } else if (ToType->isBlockPointerType()) {
3071  if (!FromType->isBlockPointerType())
3072  Kind = CK_AnyPointerToBlockPointerCast;
3073  }
3074 
3075  // We shouldn't fall into this case unless it's valid for other
3076  // reasons.
3077  if (From->isNullPointerConstant(Context, Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNull))
3078  Kind = CK_NullToPointer;
3079 
3080  return false;
3081 }

3083 /// IsMemberPointerConversion - Determines whether the conversion of the
3084 /// expression From, which has the (possibly adjusted) type FromType, can be
3085 /// converted to the type ToType via a member pointer conversion (C++ 4.11).
3086 /// If so, returns true and places the converted type (that might differ from
3087 /// ToType in its cv-qualifiers at some level) into ConvertedType.
3088 bool Sema::IsMemberPointerConversion(Expr *From, QualType FromType,
3089  QualType ToType,
3090  bool InOverloadResolution,
3091  QualType &ConvertedType) {
3092  const MemberPointerType *ToTypePtr = ToType->getAs<MemberPointerType>();
3093  if (!ToTypePtr)
3094  return false;
3095 
3096  // A null pointer constant can be converted to a member pointer (C++ 4.11p1)
3097  if (From->isNullPointerConstant(Context,
3098  InOverloadResolution? Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNotNull
3099  : Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNull)) {
3100  ConvertedType = ToType;
3101  return true;
3102  }
3103 
3104  // Otherwise, both types have to be member pointers.
3105  const MemberPointerType *FromTypePtr = FromType->getAs<MemberPointerType>();
3106  if (!FromTypePtr)
3107  return false;
3108 
3109  // A pointer to member of B can be converted to a pointer to member of D,
3110  // where D is derived from B (C++ 4.11p2).
3111  QualType FromClass(FromTypePtr->getClass(), 0);
3112  QualType ToClass(ToTypePtr->getClass(), 0);
3113 
3114  if (!Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromClass, ToClass) &&
3115  IsDerivedFrom(From->getBeginLoc(), ToClass, FromClass)) {
3116  ConvertedType = Context.getMemberPointerType(FromTypePtr->getPointeeType(),
3117  ToClass.getTypePtr());
3118  return true;
3119  }
3120 
3121  return false;
3122 }

3124 /// CheckMemberPointerConversion - Check the member pointer conversion from the
3125 /// expression From to the type ToType. This routine checks for ambiguous or
3126 /// virtual or inaccessible base-to-derived member pointer conversions
3127 /// for which IsMemberPointerConversion has already returned true. It returns
3128 /// true and produces a diagnostic if there was an error, or returns false
3129 /// otherwise.
3130 bool Sema::CheckMemberPointerConversion(Expr *From, QualType ToType,
3131  CastKind &Kind,
3132  CXXCastPath &BasePath,
3133  bool IgnoreBaseAccess) {
3134  QualType FromType = From->getType();
3135  const MemberPointerType *FromPtrType = FromType->getAs<MemberPointerType>();
3136  if (!FromPtrType) {
3137  // This must be a null pointer to member pointer conversion
3138  assert(From->isNullPointerConstant(Context,
3139  Expr::NPC_ValueDependentIsNull) &&
3140  "Expr must be null pointer constant!");
3141  Kind = CK_NullToMemberPointer;
3142  return false;
3143  }
3144 
3145  const MemberPointerType *ToPtrType = ToType->getAs<MemberPointerType>();
3146  assert(ToPtrType && "No member pointer cast has a target type "
3147  "that is not a member pointer.");
3148 
3149  QualType FromClass = QualType(FromPtrType->getClass(), 0);
3150  QualType ToClass = QualType(ToPtrType->getClass(), 0);
3151 
3152  // FIXME: What about dependent types?
3153  assert(FromClass->isRecordType() && "Pointer into non-class.");
3154  assert(ToClass->isRecordType() && "Pointer into non-class.");
3155 
3156  CXXBasePaths Paths(/*FindAmbiguities=*/true, /*RecordPaths=*/true,
3157  /*DetectVirtual=*/true);
3158  bool DerivationOkay =
3159  IsDerivedFrom(From->getBeginLoc(), ToClass, FromClass, Paths);
3160  assert(DerivationOkay &&
3161  "Should not have been called if derivation isn't OK.");
3162  (void)DerivationOkay;
3163 
3164  if (Paths.isAmbiguous(Context.getCanonicalType(FromClass).
3165  getUnqualifiedType())) {
3166  std::string PathDisplayStr = getAmbiguousPathsDisplayString(Paths);
3167  Diag(From->getExprLoc(), diag::err_ambiguous_memptr_conv)
3168  << 0 << FromClass << ToClass << PathDisplayStr << From->getSourceRange();
3169  return true;
3170  }
3171 
3172  if (const RecordType *VBase = Paths.getDetectedVirtual()) {
3173  Diag(From->getExprLoc(), diag::err_memptr_conv_via_virtual)
3174  << FromClass << ToClass << QualType(VBase, 0)
3175  << From->getSourceRange();
3176  return true;
3177  }
3178 
3179  if (!IgnoreBaseAccess)
3180  CheckBaseClassAccess(From->getExprLoc(), FromClass, ToClass,
3181  Paths.front(),
3182  diag::err_downcast_from_inaccessible_base);
3183 
3184  // Must be a base to derived member conversion.
3185  BuildBasePathArray(Paths, BasePath);
3186  Kind = CK_BaseToDerivedMemberPointer;
3187  return false;
3188 }

3190 /// Determine whether the lifetime conversion between the two given
3191 /// qualifiers sets is nontrivial.
3192 static bool isNonTrivialObjCLifetimeConversion(Qualifiers FromQuals,
3193  Qualifiers ToQuals) {
3194  // Converting anything to const __unsafe_unretained is trivial.
3195  if (ToQuals.hasConst() &&
3196  ToQuals.getObjCLifetime() == Qualifiers::OCL_ExplicitNone)
3197  return false;
3198 
3199  return true;
3200 }
3201 
3202 /// Perform a single iteration of the loop for checking if a qualification
3203 /// conversion is valid.
3204 ///
3205 /// Specifically, check whether any change between the qualifiers of \p
3206 /// FromType and \p ToType is permissible, given knowledge about whether every
3207 /// outer layer is const-qualified.
3208 static bool isQualificationConversionStep(QualType FromType, QualType ToType,
3209  bool CStyle, bool IsTopLevel,
3210  bool &PreviousToQualsIncludeConst,
3211  bool &ObjCLifetimeConversion) {
3212  Qualifiers FromQuals = FromType.getQualifiers();
3213  Qualifiers ToQuals = ToType.getQualifiers();
3214 
3215  // Ignore __unaligned qualifier.
3216  FromQuals.removeUnaligned();
3217 
3218  // Objective-C ARC:
3219  // Check Objective-C lifetime conversions.
3220  if (FromQuals.getObjCLifetime() != ToQuals.getObjCLifetime()) {
3221  if (ToQuals.compatiblyIncludesObjCLifetime(FromQuals)) {
3222  if (isNonTrivialObjCLifetimeConversion(FromQuals, ToQuals))
3223  ObjCLifetimeConversion = true;
3224  FromQuals.removeObjCLifetime();
3225  ToQuals.removeObjCLifetime();
3226  } else {
3227  // Qualification conversions cannot cast between different
3228  // Objective-C lifetime qualifiers.
3229  return false;
3230  }
3231  }
3232 
3233  // Allow addition/removal of GC attributes but not changing GC attributes.
3234  if (FromQuals.getObjCGCAttr() != ToQuals.getObjCGCAttr() &&
3235  (!FromQuals.hasObjCGCAttr() || !ToQuals.hasObjCGCAttr())) {
3236  FromQuals.removeObjCGCAttr();
3237  ToQuals.removeObjCGCAttr();
3238  }
3239 
3240  // -- for every j > 0, if const is in cv 1,j then const is in cv
3241  // 2,j, and similarly for volatile.
3242  if (!CStyle && !ToQuals.compatiblyIncludes(FromQuals))
3243  return false;
3244 
3245  // If address spaces mismatch:
3246  // - in top level it is only valid to convert to addr space that is a
3247  // superset in all cases apart from C-style casts where we allow
3248  // conversions between overlapping address spaces.
3249  // - in non-top levels it is not a valid conversion.
3250  if (ToQuals.getAddressSpace() != FromQuals.getAddressSpace() &&
3251  (!IsTopLevel ||
3252  !(ToQuals.isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(FromQuals) ||
3253  (CStyle && FromQuals.isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(ToQuals)))))
3254  return false;
3255 
3256  // -- if the cv 1,j and cv 2,j are different, then const is in
3257  // every cv for 0 < k < j.
3258  if (!CStyle && FromQuals.getCVRQualifiers() != ToQuals.getCVRQualifiers() &&
3259  !PreviousToQualsIncludeConst)
3260  return false;
3261 
3262  // The following wording is from C++20, where the result of the conversion
3263  // is T3, not T2.
3264  // -- if [...] P1,i [...] is "array of unknown bound of", P3,i is
3265  // "array of unknown bound of"
3266  if (FromType->isIncompleteArrayType() && !ToType->isIncompleteArrayType())
3267  return false;
3268 
3269  // -- if the resulting P3,i is different from P1,i [...], then const is
3270  // added to every cv 3_k for 0 < k < i.
3271  if (!CStyle && FromType->isConstantArrayType() &&
3272  ToType->isIncompleteArrayType() && !PreviousToQualsIncludeConst)
3273  return false;
3274 
3275  // Keep track of whether all prior cv-qualifiers in the "to" type
3276  // include const.
3277  PreviousToQualsIncludeConst =
3278  PreviousToQualsIncludeConst && ToQuals.hasConst();
3279  return true;
3280 }
3281 
3282 /// IsQualificationConversion - Determines whether the conversion from
3283 /// an rvalue of type FromType to ToType is a qualification conversion
3284 /// (C++ 4.4).
3285 ///
3286 /// \param ObjCLifetimeConversion Output parameter that will be set to indicate
3287 /// when the qualification conversion involves a change in the Objective-C
3288 /// object lifetime.
3289 bool
3290 Sema::IsQualificationConversion(QualType FromType, QualType ToType,
3291  bool CStyle, bool &ObjCLifetimeConversion) {
3292  FromType = Context.getCanonicalType(FromType);
3293  ToType = Context.getCanonicalType(ToType);
3294  ObjCLifetimeConversion = false;
3295 
3296  // If FromType and ToType are the same type, this is not a
3297  // qualification conversion.
3298  if (FromType.getUnqualifiedType() == ToType.getUnqualifiedType())
3299  return false;
3300 
3301  // (C++ 4.4p4):
3302  // A conversion can add cv-qualifiers at levels other than the first
3303  // in multi-level pointers, subject to the following rules: [...]
3304  bool PreviousToQualsIncludeConst = true;
3305  bool UnwrappedAnyPointer = false;
3306  while (Context.UnwrapSimilarTypes(FromType, ToType)) {
3307  if (!isQualificationConversionStep(
3308  FromType, ToType, CStyle, !UnwrappedAnyPointer,
3309  PreviousToQualsIncludeConst, ObjCLifetimeConversion))
3310  return false;
3311  UnwrappedAnyPointer = true;
3312  }
3313 
3314  // We are left with FromType and ToType being the pointee types
3315  // after unwrapping the original FromType and ToType the same number
3316  // of times. If we unwrapped any pointers, and if FromType and
3317  // ToType have the same unqualified type (since we checked
3318  // qualifiers above), then this is a qualification conversion.
3319  return UnwrappedAnyPointer && Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromType,ToType);
3320 }
3321 
3322 /// - Determine whether this is a conversion from a scalar type to an
3323 /// atomic type.
3324 ///
3325 /// If successful, updates \c SCS's second and third steps in the conversion
3326 /// sequence to finish the conversion.
3327 static bool tryAtomicConversion(Sema &S, Expr *From, QualType ToType,
3328  bool InOverloadResolution,
3329  StandardConversionSequence &SCS,
3330  bool CStyle) {
3331  const AtomicType *ToAtomic = ToType->getAs<AtomicType>();
3332  if (!ToAtomic)
3333  return false;
3334 
3335  StandardConversionSequence InnerSCS;
3336  if (!IsStandardConversion(S, From, ToAtomic->getValueType(),
3337  InOverloadResolution, InnerSCS,
3338  CStyle, /*AllowObjCWritebackConversion=*/false))
3339  return false;
3340 
3341  SCS.Second = InnerSCS.Second;
3342  SCS.setToType(1, InnerSCS.getToType(1));
3343  SCS.Third = InnerSCS.Third;
3344  SCS.QualificationIncludesObjCLifetime
3345  = InnerSCS.QualificationIncludesObjCLifetime;
3346  SCS.setToType(2, InnerSCS.getToType(2));
3347  return true;
3348 }

3350 static bool isFirstArgumentCompatibleWithType(ASTContext &Context,
3351  CXXConstructorDecl *Constructor,
3352  QualType Type) {
3353  const auto *CtorType = Constructor->getType()->castAs<FunctionProtoType>();
3354  if (CtorType->getNumParams() > 0) {
3355  QualType FirstArg = CtorType->getParamType(0);
3356  if (Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(Type, FirstArg.getNonReferenceType()))
3357  return true;
3358  }
3359  return false;
3360 }

3362 static OverloadingResult
3363 IsInitializerListConstructorConversion(Sema &S, Expr *From, QualType ToType,
3364  CXXRecordDecl *To,
3365  UserDefinedConversionSequence &User,
3366  OverloadCandidateSet &CandidateSet,
3367  bool AllowExplicit) {
3368  CandidateSet.clear(OverloadCandidateSet::CSK_InitByUserDefinedConversion);
3369  for (auto *D : S.LookupConstructors(To)) {
3370  auto Info = getConstructorInfo(D);
3371  if (!Info)
3372  continue;
3373 
3374  bool Usable = !Info.Constructor->isInvalidDecl() &&
3375  S.isInitListConstructor(Info.Constructor);
3376  if (Usable) {
3377  bool SuppressUserConversions = false;
3378  if (Info.ConstructorTmpl)
3379  S.AddTemplateOverloadCandidate(Info.ConstructorTmpl, Info.FoundDecl,
3380  /*ExplicitArgs*/ nullptr, From,
3381  CandidateSet, SuppressUserConversions,
3382  /*PartialOverloading*/ false,
3383  AllowExplicit);
3384  else
3385  S.AddOverloadCandidate(Info.Constructor, Info.FoundDecl, From,
3386  CandidateSet, SuppressUserConversions,
3387  /*PartialOverloading*/ false, AllowExplicit);
3388  }
3389  }
3390 
3391  bool HadMultipleCandidates = (CandidateSet.size() > 1);
3392 
3393  OverloadCandidateSet::iterator Best;
3394  switch (auto Result =
3395  CandidateSet.BestViableFunction(S, From->getBeginLoc(), Best)) {
3396  case OR_Deleted:
3397  case OR_Success: {
3398  // Record the standard conversion we used and the conversion function.
3399  CXXConstructorDecl *Constructor = cast<CXXConstructorDecl>(Best->Function);
3400  QualType ThisType = Constructor->getThisType();
3401  // Initializer lists don't have conversions as such.
3402  User.Before.setAsIdentityConversion();
3403  User.HadMultipleCandidates = HadMultipleCandidates;
3404  User.ConversionFunction = Constructor;
3405  User.FoundConversionFunction = Best->FoundDecl;
3406  User.After.setAsIdentityConversion();
3407  User.After.setFromType(ThisType->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType());
3408  User.After.setAllToTypes(ToType);
3409  return Result;
3410  }
3411 
3412  case OR_No_Viable_Function:
3413  return OR_No_Viable_Function;
3414  case OR_Ambiguous:
3415  return OR_Ambiguous;
3416  }
3417 
3418  llvm_unreachable("Invalid OverloadResult!");
3419 }

3421 /// Determines whether there is a user-defined conversion sequence
3422 /// (C++ [over.ics.user]) that converts expression From to the type
3423 /// ToType. If such a conversion exists, User will contain the
3424 /// user-defined conversion sequence that performs such a conversion
3425 /// and this routine will return true. Otherwise, this routine returns
3426 /// false and User is unspecified.
3427 ///
3428 /// \param AllowExplicit true if the conversion should consider C++0x
3429 /// "explicit" conversion functions as well as non-explicit conversion
3430 /// functions (C++0x [class.conv.fct]p2).
3431 ///
3432 /// \param AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit true if the conversion should
3433 /// allow an extra Objective-C pointer conversion on uses of explicit
3434 /// constructors. Requires \c AllowExplicit to also be set.
3435 static OverloadingResult
3436 IsUserDefinedConversion(Sema &S, Expr *From, QualType ToType,
3437  UserDefinedConversionSequence &User,
3438  OverloadCandidateSet &CandidateSet,
3439  AllowedExplicit AllowExplicit,
3440  bool AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit) {
3441  assert(AllowExplicit != AllowedExplicit::None ||
3442  !AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit);
3443  CandidateSet.clear(OverloadCandidateSet::CSK_InitByUserDefinedConversion);
3444 
3445  // Whether we will only visit constructors.
3446  bool ConstructorsOnly = false;
3447 
3448  // If the type we are conversion to is a class type, enumerate its
3449  // constructors.
3450  if (const RecordType *ToRecordType = ToType->getAs<RecordType>()) {
3451  // C++ [over.match.ctor]p1:
3452  // When objects of class type are direct-initialized (8.5), or
3453  // copy-initialized from an expression of the same or a
3454  // derived class type (8.5), overload resolution selects the
3455  // constructor. [...] For copy-initialization, the candidate
3456  // functions are all the converting constructors (12.3.1) of
3457  // that class. The argument list is the expression-list within
3458  // the parentheses of the initializer.
3459  if (S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ToType, From->getType()) ||
3460  (From->getType()->getAs<RecordType>() &&
3461  S.IsDerivedFrom(From->getBeginLoc(), From->getType(), ToType)))
3462  ConstructorsOnly = true;
3463 
3464  if (!S.isCompleteType(From->getExprLoc(), ToType)) {
3465  // We're not going to find any constructors.
3466  } else if (CXXRecordDecl *ToRecordDecl
3467  = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(ToRecordType->getDecl())) {
3468 
3469  Expr **Args = &From;
3470  unsigned NumArgs = 1;
3471  bool ListInitializing = false;
3472  if (InitListExpr *InitList = dyn_cast<InitListExpr>(From)) {
3473  // But first, see if there is an init-list-constructor that will work.
3474  OverloadingResult Result = IsInitializerListConstructorConversion(
3475  S, From, ToType, ToRecordDecl, User, CandidateSet,
3476  AllowExplicit == AllowedExplicit::All);
3477  if (Result != OR_No_Viable_Function)
3478  return Result;
3479  // Never mind.
3480  CandidateSet.clear(
3481  OverloadCandidateSet::CSK_InitByUserDefinedConversion);
3482 
3483  // If we're list-initializing, we pass the individual elements as
3484  // arguments, not the entire list.
3485  Args = InitList->getInits();
3486  NumArgs = InitList->getNumInits();
3487  ListInitializing = true;
3488  }
3489 
3490  for (auto *D : S.LookupConstructors(ToRecordDecl)) {
3491  auto Info = getConstructorInfo(D);
3492  if (!Info)
3493  continue;
3494 
3495  bool Usable = !Info.Constructor->isInvalidDecl();
3496  if (!ListInitializing)
3497  Usable = Usable && Info.Constructor->isConvertingConstructor(
3498  /*AllowExplicit*/ true);
3499  if (Usable) {
3500  bool SuppressUserConversions = !ConstructorsOnly;
3501  // C++20 [over.best.ics.general]/4.5:
3502  // if the target is the first parameter of a constructor [of class
3503  // X] and the constructor [...] is a candidate by [...] the second
3504  // phase of [over.match.list] when the initializer list has exactly
3505  // one element that is itself an initializer list, [...] and the
3506  // conversion is to X or reference to cv X, user-defined conversion
3507  // sequences are not cnosidered.
3508  if (SuppressUserConversions && ListInitializing) {
3509  SuppressUserConversions =
3510  NumArgs == 1 && isa<InitListExpr>(Args[0]) &&
3511  isFirstArgumentCompatibleWithType(S.Context, Info.Constructor,
3512  ToType);
3513  }
3514  if (Info.ConstructorTmpl)
3515  S.AddTemplateOverloadCandidate(
3516  Info.ConstructorTmpl, Info.FoundDecl,
3517  /*ExplicitArgs*/ nullptr, llvm::makeArrayRef(Args, NumArgs),
3518  CandidateSet, SuppressUserConversions,
3519  /*PartialOverloading*/ false,
3520  AllowExplicit == AllowedExplicit::All);
3521  else
3522  // Allow one user-defined conversion when user specifies a
3523  // From->ToType conversion via an static cast (c-style, etc).
3524  S.AddOverloadCandidate(Info.Constructor, Info.FoundDecl,
3525  llvm::makeArrayRef(Args, NumArgs),
3526  CandidateSet, SuppressUserConversions,
3527  /*PartialOverloading*/ false,
3528  AllowExplicit == AllowedExplicit::All);
3529  }
3530  }
3531  }
3532  }
3533 
3534  // Enumerate conversion functions, if we're allowed to.
3535  if (ConstructorsOnly || isa<InitListExpr>(From)) {
3536  } else if (!S.isCompleteType(From->getBeginLoc(), From->getType())) {
3537  // No conversion functions from incomplete types.
3538  } else if (const RecordType *FromRecordType =
3539  From->getType()->getAs<RecordType>()) {
3540  if (CXXRecordDecl *FromRecordDecl
3541  = dyn_cast<CXXRecordDecl>(FromRecordType->getDecl())) {
3542  // Add all of the conversion functions as candidates.
3543  const auto &Conversions = FromRecordDecl->getVisibleConversionFunctions();
3544  for (auto I = Conversions.begin(), E = Conversions.end(); I != E; ++I) {
3545  DeclAccessPair FoundDecl = I.getPair();
3546  NamedDecl *D = FoundDecl.getDecl();
3547  CXXRecordDecl *ActingContext = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(D->getDeclContext());
3548  if (isa<UsingShadowDecl>(D))
3549  D = cast<UsingShadowDecl>(D)->getTargetDecl();
3550 
3551  CXXConversionDecl *Conv;
3552  FunctionTemplateDecl *ConvTemplate;
3553  if ((ConvTemplate = dyn_cast<FunctionTemplateDecl>(D)))
3554  Conv = cast<CXXConversionDecl>(ConvTemplate->getTemplatedDecl());
3555  else
3556  Conv = cast<CXXConversionDecl>(D);
3557 
3558  if (ConvTemplate)
3559  S.AddTemplateConversionCandidate(
3560  ConvTemplate, FoundDecl, ActingContext, From, ToType,
3561  CandidateSet, AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit,
3562  AllowExplicit != AllowedExplicit::None);
3563  else
3564  S.AddConversionCandidate(Conv, FoundDecl, ActingContext, From, ToType,
3565  CandidateSet, AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit,
3566  AllowExplicit != AllowedExplicit::None);
3567  }
3568  }
3569  }
3570 
3571  bool HadMultipleCandidates = (CandidateSet.size() > 1);
3572 
3573  OverloadCandidateSet::iterator Best;
3574  switch (auto Result =
3575  CandidateSet.BestViableFunction(S, From->getBeginLoc(), Best)) {
3576  case OR_Success:
3577  case OR_Deleted:
3578  // Record the standard conversion we used and the conversion function.
3579  if (CXXConstructorDecl *Constructor
3580  = dyn_cast<CXXConstructorDecl>(Best->Function)) {
3581  // C++ [over.ics.user]p1:
3582  // If the user-defined conversion is specified by a
3583  // constructor (12.3.1), the initial standard conversion
3584  // sequence converts the source type to the type required by
3585  // the argument of the constructor.
3586  //
3587  QualType ThisType = Constructor->getThisType();
3588  if (isa<InitListExpr>(From)) {
3589  // Initializer lists don't have conversions as such.
3590  User.Before.setAsIdentityConversion();
3591  } else {
3592  if (Best->Conversions[0].isEllipsis())
3593  User.EllipsisConversion = true;
3594  else {
3595  User.Before = Best->Conversions[0].Standard;
3596  User.EllipsisConversion = false;
3597  }
3598  }
3599  User.HadMultipleCandidates = HadMultipleCandidates;
3600  User.ConversionFunction = Constructor;
3601  User.FoundConversionFunction = Best->FoundDecl;
3602  User.After.setAsIdentityConversion();
3603  User.After.setFromType(ThisType->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType());
3604  User.After.setAllToTypes(ToType);
3605  return Result;
3606  }
3607  if (CXXConversionDecl *Conversion
3608  = dyn_cast<CXXConversionDecl>(Best->Function)) {
3609  // C++ [over.ics.user]p1:
3610  //
3611  // [...] If the user-defined conversion is specified by a
3612  // conversion function (12.3.2), the initial standard
3613  // conversion sequence converts the source type to the
3614  // implicit object parameter of the conversion function.
3615  User.Before = Best->Conversions[0].Standard;
3616  User.HadMultipleCandidates = HadMultipleCandidates;
3617  User.ConversionFunction = Conversion;
3618  User.FoundConversionFunction = Best->FoundDecl;
3619  User.EllipsisConversion = false;
3620 
3621  // C++ [over.ics.user]p2:
3622  // The second standard conversion sequence converts the
3623  // result of the user-defined conversion to the target type
3624  // for the sequence. Since an implicit conversion sequence
3625  // is an initialization, the special rules for
3626  // initialization by user-defined conversion apply when
3627  // selecting the best user-defined conversion for a
3628  // user-defined conversion sequence (see 13.3.3 and
3629  // 13.3.3.1).
3630  User.After = Best->FinalConversion;
3631  return Result;
3632  }
3633  llvm_unreachable("Not a constructor or conversion function?");
3634 
3635  case OR_No_Viable_Function:
3636  return OR_No_Viable_Function;
3637 
3638  case OR_Ambiguous:
3639  return OR_Ambiguous;
3640  }
3641 
3642  llvm_unreachable("Invalid OverloadResult!");
3643 }
3644 
3645 bool
3646 Sema::DiagnoseMultipleUserDefinedConversion(Expr *From, QualType ToType) {
3647  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS;
3648  OverloadCandidateSet CandidateSet(From->getExprLoc(),
3649  OverloadCandidateSet::CSK_Normal);
3650  OverloadingResult OvResult =
3651  IsUserDefinedConversion(*this, From, ToType, ICS.UserDefined,
3652  CandidateSet, AllowedExplicit::None, false);
3653 
3654  if (!(OvResult == OR_Ambiguous ||
3655  (OvResult == OR_No_Viable_Function && !CandidateSet.empty())))
3656  return false;
3657 
3658  auto Cands = CandidateSet.CompleteCandidates(
3659  *this,
3660  OvResult == OR_Ambiguous ? OCD_AmbiguousCandidates : OCD_AllCandidates,
3661  From);
3662  if (OvResult == OR_Ambiguous)
3663  Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_typecheck_ambiguous_condition)
3664  << From->getType() << ToType << From->getSourceRange();
3665  else { // OR_No_Viable_Function && !CandidateSet.empty()
3666  if (!RequireCompleteType(From->getBeginLoc(), ToType,
3667  diag::err_typecheck_nonviable_condition_incomplete,
3668  From->getType(), From->getSourceRange()))
3669  Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_typecheck_nonviable_condition)
3670  << false << From->getType() << From->getSourceRange() << ToType;
3671  }
3672 
3673  CandidateSet.NoteCandidates(
3674  *this, From, Cands);
3675  return true;
3676 }
3677 
3678 // Helper for compareConversionFunctions that gets the FunctionType that the
3679 // conversion-operator return value 'points' to, or nullptr.
3680 static const FunctionType *
3681 getConversionOpReturnTyAsFunction(CXXConversionDecl *Conv) {
3682  const FunctionType *ConvFuncTy = Conv->getType()->castAs<FunctionType>();
3683  const PointerType *RetPtrTy =
3684  ConvFuncTy->getReturnType()->getAs<PointerType>();
3685 
3686  if (!RetPtrTy)
3687  return nullptr;
3688 
3689  return RetPtrTy->getPointeeType()->getAs<FunctionType>();
3690 }
3691 
3692 /// Compare the user-defined conversion functions or constructors
3693 /// of two user-defined conversion sequences to determine whether any ordering
3694 /// is possible.
3695 static ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind
3696 compareConversionFunctions(Sema &S, FunctionDecl *Function1,
3697  FunctionDecl *Function2) {
3698  CXXConversionDecl *Conv1 = dyn_cast_or_null<CXXConversionDecl>(Function1);
3699  CXXConversionDecl *Conv2 = dyn_cast_or_null<CXXConversionDecl>(Function2);
3700  if (!Conv1 || !Conv2)
3701  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3702 
3703  if (!Conv1->getParent()->isLambda() || !Conv2->getParent()->isLambda())
3704  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3705 
3706  // Objective-C++:
3707  // If both conversion functions are implicitly-declared conversions from
3708  // a lambda closure type to a function pointer and a block pointer,
3709  // respectively, always prefer the conversion to a function pointer,
3710  // because the function pointer is more lightweight and is more likely
3711  // to keep code working.
3712  if (S.getLangOpts().ObjC && S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11) {
3713  bool Block1 = Conv1->getConversionType()->isBlockPointerType();
3714  bool Block2 = Conv2->getConversionType()->isBlockPointerType();
3715  if (Block1 != Block2)
3716  return Block1 ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse
3717  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3718  }
3719 
3720  // In order to support multiple calling conventions for the lambda conversion
3721  // operator (such as when the free and member function calling convention is
3722  // different), prefer the 'free' mechanism, followed by the calling-convention
3723  // of operator(). The latter is in place to support the MSVC-like solution of
3724  // defining ALL of the possible conversions in regards to calling-convention.
3725  const FunctionType *Conv1FuncRet = getConversionOpReturnTyAsFunction(Conv1);
3726  const FunctionType *Conv2FuncRet = getConversionOpReturnTyAsFunction(Conv2);
3727 
3728  if (Conv1FuncRet && Conv2FuncRet &&
3729  Conv1FuncRet->getCallConv() != Conv2FuncRet->getCallConv()) {
3730  CallingConv Conv1CC = Conv1FuncRet->getCallConv();
3731  CallingConv Conv2CC = Conv2FuncRet->getCallConv();
3732 
3733  CXXMethodDecl *CallOp = Conv2->getParent()->getLambdaCallOperator();
3734  const auto *CallOpProto = CallOp->getType()->castAs<FunctionProtoType>();
3735 
3736  CallingConv CallOpCC =
3737  CallOp->getType()->castAs<FunctionType>()->getCallConv();
3738  CallingConv DefaultFree = S.Context.getDefaultCallingConvention(
3739  CallOpProto->isVariadic(), /*IsCXXMethod=*/false);
3740  CallingConv DefaultMember = S.Context.getDefaultCallingConvention(
3741  CallOpProto->isVariadic(), /*IsCXXMethod=*/true);
3742 
3743  CallingConv PrefOrder[] = {DefaultFree, DefaultMember, CallOpCC};
3744  for (CallingConv CC : PrefOrder) {
3745  if (Conv1CC == CC)
3746  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3747  if (Conv2CC == CC)
3748  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3749  }
3750  }
3751 
3752  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3753 }
3754 
3755 static bool hasDeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtrConversion(
3756  const ImplicitConversionSequence &ICS) {
3757  return (ICS.isStandard() && ICS.Standard.DeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtr) ||
3758  (ICS.isUserDefined() &&
3759  ICS.UserDefined.Before.DeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtr);
3760 }
3761 
3762 /// CompareImplicitConversionSequences - Compare two implicit
3763 /// conversion sequences to determine whether one is better than the
3764 /// other or if they are indistinguishable (C++ 13.3.3.2).
3765 static ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind
3766 CompareImplicitConversionSequences(Sema &S, SourceLocation Loc,
3767  const ImplicitConversionSequence& ICS1,
3768  const ImplicitConversionSequence& ICS2)
3769 {
3770  // (C++ 13.3.3.2p2): When comparing the basic forms of implicit
3771  // conversion sequences (as defined in 13.3.3.1)
3772  // -- a standard conversion sequence (13.3.3.1.1) is a better
3773  // conversion sequence than a user-defined conversion sequence or
3774  // an ellipsis conversion sequence, and
3775  // -- a user-defined conversion sequence (13.3.3.1.2) is a better
3776  // conversion sequence than an ellipsis conversion sequence
3777  // (13.3.3.1.3).
3778  //
3779  // C++0x [over.best.ics]p10:
3780  // For the purpose of ranking implicit conversion sequences as
3781  // described in 13.3.3.2, the ambiguous conversion sequence is
3782  // treated as a user-defined sequence that is indistinguishable
3783  // from any other user-defined conversion sequence.
3784 
3785  // String literal to 'char *' conversion has been deprecated in C++03. It has
3786  // been removed from C++11. We still accept this conversion, if it happens at
3787  // the best viable function. Otherwise, this conversion is considered worse
3788  // than ellipsis conversion. Consider this as an extension; this is not in the
3789  // standard. For example:
3790  //
3791  // int &f(...); // #1
3792  // void f(char*); // #2
3793  // void g() { int &r = f("foo"); }
3794  //
3795  // In C++03, we pick #2 as the best viable function.
3796  // In C++11, we pick #1 as the best viable function, because ellipsis
3797  // conversion is better than string-literal to char* conversion (since there
3798  // is no such conversion in C++11). If there was no #1 at all or #1 couldn't
3799  // convert arguments, #2 would be the best viable function in C++11.
3800  // If the best viable function has this conversion, a warning will be issued
3801  // in C++03, or an ExtWarn (+SFINAE failure) will be issued in C++11.
3802 
3803  if (S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 && !S.getLangOpts().WritableStrings &&
3804  hasDeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtrConversion(ICS1) !=
3805  hasDeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtrConversion(ICS2) &&
3806  // Ill-formedness must not differ
3807  ICS1.isBad() == ICS2.isBad())
3808  return hasDeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtrConversion(ICS1)
3809  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse
3810  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3811 
3812  if (ICS1.getKindRank() < ICS2.getKindRank())
3813  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3814  if (ICS2.getKindRank() < ICS1.getKindRank())
3815  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3816 
3817  // The following checks require both conversion sequences to be of
3818  // the same kind.
3819  if (ICS1.getKind() != ICS2.getKind())
3820  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3821 
3822  ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind Result =
3823  ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3824 
3825  // Two implicit conversion sequences of the same form are
3826  // indistinguishable conversion sequences unless one of the
3827  // following rules apply: (C++ 13.3.3.2p3):
3828 
3829  // List-initialization sequence L1 is a better conversion sequence than
3830  // list-initialization sequence L2 if:
3831  // - L1 converts to std::initializer_list<X> for some X and L2 does not, or,
3832  // if not that,
3833  // L1 and L2 convert to arrays of the same element type, and either the
3834  // number of elements n_1 initialized by L1 is less than the number of
3835  // elements n_2 initialized by L2, or (C++20) n_1 = n_2 and L2 converts to
3836  // an array of unknown bound and L1 does not,
3837  // even if one of the other rules in this paragraph would otherwise apply.
3838  if (!ICS1.isBad()) {
3839  bool StdInit1 = false, StdInit2 = false;
3840  if (ICS1.hasInitializerListContainerType())
3841  StdInit1 = S.isStdInitializerList(ICS1.getInitializerListContainerType(),
3842  nullptr);
3843  if (ICS2.hasInitializerListContainerType())
3844  StdInit2 = S.isStdInitializerList(ICS2.getInitializerListContainerType(),
3845  nullptr);
3846  if (StdInit1 != StdInit2)
3847  return StdInit1 ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
3848  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3849 
3850  if (ICS1.hasInitializerListContainerType() &&
3851  ICS2.hasInitializerListContainerType())
3852  if (auto *CAT1 = S.Context.getAsConstantArrayType(
3853  ICS1.getInitializerListContainerType()))
3854  if (auto *CAT2 = S.Context.getAsConstantArrayType(
3855  ICS2.getInitializerListContainerType())) {
3856  if (S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(CAT1->getElementType(),
3857  CAT2->getElementType())) {
3858  // Both to arrays of the same element type
3859  if (CAT1->getSize() != CAT2->getSize())
3860  // Different sized, the smaller wins
3861  return CAT1->getSize().ult(CAT2->getSize())
3862  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
3863  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3864  if (ICS1.isInitializerListOfIncompleteArray() !=
3865  ICS2.isInitializerListOfIncompleteArray())
3866  // One is incomplete, it loses
3867  return ICS2.isInitializerListOfIncompleteArray()
3868  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
3869  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3870  }
3871  }
3872  }
3873 
3874  if (ICS1.isStandard())
3875  // Standard conversion sequence S1 is a better conversion sequence than
3876  // standard conversion sequence S2 if [...]
3877  Result = CompareStandardConversionSequences(S, Loc,
3878  ICS1.Standard, ICS2.Standard);
3879  else if (ICS1.isUserDefined()) {
3880  // User-defined conversion sequence U1 is a better conversion
3881  // sequence than another user-defined conversion sequence U2 if
3882  // they contain the same user-defined conversion function or
3883  // constructor and if the second standard conversion sequence of
3884  // U1 is better than the second standard conversion sequence of
3885  // U2 (C++ 13.3.3.2p3).
3886  if (ICS1.UserDefined.ConversionFunction ==
3887  ICS2.UserDefined.ConversionFunction)
3888  Result = CompareStandardConversionSequences(S, Loc,
3889  ICS1.UserDefined.After,
3890  ICS2.UserDefined.After);
3891  else
3892  Result = compareConversionFunctions(S,
3893  ICS1.UserDefined.ConversionFunction,
3894  ICS2.UserDefined.ConversionFunction);
3895  }
3896 
3897  return Result;
3898 }
3899 
3900 // Per 13.3.3.2p3, compare the given standard conversion sequences to
3901 // determine if one is a proper subset of the other.
3902 static ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind
3903 compareStandardConversionSubsets(ASTContext &Context,
3904  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS1,
3905  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS2) {
3906  ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind Result
3907  = ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3908 
3909  // the identity conversion sequence is considered to be a subsequence of
3910  // any non-identity conversion sequence
3911  if (SCS1.isIdentityConversion() && !SCS2.isIdentityConversion())
3912  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3913  else if (!SCS1.isIdentityConversion() && SCS2.isIdentityConversion())
3914  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3915 
3916  if (SCS1.Second != SCS2.Second) {
3917  if (SCS1.Second == ICK_Identity)
3918  Result = ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3919  else if (SCS2.Second == ICK_Identity)
3920  Result = ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3921  else
3922  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3923  } else if (!Context.hasSimilarType(SCS1.getToType(1), SCS2.getToType(1)))
3924  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3925 
3926  if (SCS1.Third == SCS2.Third) {
3927  return Context.hasSameType(SCS1.getToType(2), SCS2.getToType(2))? Result
3928  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3929  }
3930 
3931  if (SCS1.Third == ICK_Identity)
3932  return Result == ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse
3933  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable
3934  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
3935 
3936  if (SCS2.Third == ICK_Identity)
3937  return Result == ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
3938  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable
3939  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
3940 
3941  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
3942 }
3943 
3944 /// Determine whether one of the given reference bindings is better
3945 /// than the other based on what kind of bindings they are.
3946 static bool
3947 isBetterReferenceBindingKind(const StandardConversionSequence &SCS1,
3948  const StandardConversionSequence &SCS2) {
3949  // C++0x [over.ics.rank]p3b4:
3950  // -- S1 and S2 are reference bindings (8.5.3) and neither refers to an
3951  // implicit object parameter of a non-static member function declared
3952  // without a ref-qualifier, and *either* S1 binds an rvalue reference
3953  // to an rvalue and S2 binds an lvalue reference *or S1 binds an
3954  // lvalue reference to a function lvalue and S2 binds an rvalue
3955  // reference*.
3956  //
3957  // FIXME: Rvalue references. We're going rogue with the above edits,
3958  // because the semantics in the current C++0x working paper (N3225 at the
3959  // time of this writing) break the standard definition of std::forward
3960  // and std::reference_wrapper when dealing with references to functions.
3961  // Proposed wording changes submitted to CWG for consideration.
3962  if (SCS1.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier ||
3963  SCS2.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier)
3964  return false;
3965 
3966  return (!SCS1.IsLvalueReference && SCS1.BindsToRvalue &&
3967  SCS2.IsLvalueReference) ||
3968  (SCS1.IsLvalueReference && SCS1.BindsToFunctionLvalue &&
3969  !SCS2.IsLvalueReference && SCS2.BindsToFunctionLvalue);
3970 }
3971 
3972 enum class FixedEnumPromotion {
3973  None,
3974  ToUnderlyingType,
3975  ToPromotedUnderlyingType
3976 };
3977 
3978 /// Returns kind of fixed enum promotion the \a SCS uses.
3979 static FixedEnumPromotion
3980 getFixedEnumPromtion(Sema &S, const StandardConversionSequence &SCS) {
3981 
3982  if (SCS.Second != ICK_Integral_Promotion)
3983  return FixedEnumPromotion::None;
3984 
3985  QualType FromType = SCS.getFromType();
3986  if (!FromType->isEnumeralType())
3987  return FixedEnumPromotion::None;
3988 
3989  EnumDecl *Enum = FromType->castAs<EnumType>()->getDecl();
3990  if (!Enum->isFixed())
3991  return FixedEnumPromotion::None;
3992 
3993  QualType UnderlyingType = Enum->getIntegerType();
3994  if (S.Context.hasSameType(SCS.getToType(1), UnderlyingType))
3995  return FixedEnumPromotion::ToUnderlyingType;
3996 
3997  return FixedEnumPromotion::ToPromotedUnderlyingType;
3998 }
3999 
4000 /// CompareStandardConversionSequences - Compare two standard
4001 /// conversion sequences to determine whether one is better than the
4002 /// other or if they are indistinguishable (C++ 13.3.3.2p3).
4003 static ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind
4004 CompareStandardConversionSequences(Sema &S, SourceLocation Loc,
4005  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS1,
4006  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS2)
4007 {
4008  // Standard conversion sequence S1 is a better conversion sequence
4009  // than standard conversion sequence S2 if (C++ 13.3.3.2p3):
4010 
4011  // -- S1 is a proper subsequence of S2 (comparing the conversion
4012  // sequences in the canonical form defined by 13.3.3.1.1,
4013  // excluding any Lvalue Transformation; the identity conversion
4014  // sequence is considered to be a subsequence of any
4015  // non-identity conversion sequence) or, if not that,
4016  if (ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind CK
4017  = compareStandardConversionSubsets(S.Context, SCS1, SCS2))
4018  return CK;
4019 
4020  // -- the rank of S1 is better than the rank of S2 (by the rules
4021  // defined below), or, if not that,
4022  ImplicitConversionRank Rank1 = SCS1.getRank();
4023  ImplicitConversionRank Rank2 = SCS2.getRank();
4024  if (Rank1 < Rank2)
4025  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4026  else if (Rank2 < Rank1)
4027  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4028 
4029  // (C++ 13.3.3.2p4): Two conversion sequences with the same rank
4030  // are indistinguishable unless one of the following rules
4031  // applies:
4032 
4033  // A conversion that is not a conversion of a pointer, or
4034  // pointer to member, to bool is better than another conversion
4035  // that is such a conversion.
4036  if (SCS1.isPointerConversionToBool() != SCS2.isPointerConversionToBool())
4037  return SCS2.isPointerConversionToBool()
4038  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4039  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4040 
4041  // C++14 [over.ics.rank]p4b2:
4042  // This is retroactively applied to C++11 by CWG 1601.
4043  //
4044  // A conversion that promotes an enumeration whose underlying type is fixed
4045  // to its underlying type is better than one that promotes to the promoted
4046  // underlying type, if the two are different.
4047  FixedEnumPromotion FEP1 = getFixedEnumPromtion(S, SCS1);
4048  FixedEnumPromotion FEP2 = getFixedEnumPromtion(S, SCS2);
4049  if (FEP1 != FixedEnumPromotion::None && FEP2 != FixedEnumPromotion::None &&
4050  FEP1 != FEP2)
4051  return FEP1 == FixedEnumPromotion::ToUnderlyingType
4052  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4053  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4054 
4055  // C++ [over.ics.rank]p4b2:
4056  //
4057  // If class B is derived directly or indirectly from class A,
4058  // conversion of B* to A* is better than conversion of B* to
4059  // void*, and conversion of A* to void* is better than conversion
4060  // of B* to void*.
4061  bool SCS1ConvertsToVoid
4062  = SCS1.isPointerConversionToVoidPointer(S.Context);
4063  bool SCS2ConvertsToVoid
4064  = SCS2.isPointerConversionToVoidPointer(S.Context);
4065  if (SCS1ConvertsToVoid != SCS2ConvertsToVoid) {
4066  // Exactly one of the conversion sequences is a conversion to
4067  // a void pointer; it's the worse conversion.
4068  return SCS2ConvertsToVoid ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4069  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4070  } else if (!SCS1ConvertsToVoid && !SCS2ConvertsToVoid) {
4071  // Neither conversion sequence converts to a void pointer; compare
4072  // their derived-to-base conversions.
4073  if (ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind DerivedCK
