4074  = CompareDerivedToBaseConversions(S, Loc, SCS1, SCS2))
4075  return DerivedCK;
4076  } else if (SCS1ConvertsToVoid && SCS2ConvertsToVoid &&
4077  !S.Context.hasSameType(SCS1.getFromType(), SCS2.getFromType())) {
4078  // Both conversion sequences are conversions to void
4079  // pointers. Compare the source types to determine if there's an
4080  // inheritance relationship in their sources.
4081  QualType FromType1 = SCS1.getFromType();
4082  QualType FromType2 = SCS2.getFromType();
4083 
4084  // Adjust the types we're converting from via the array-to-pointer
4085  // conversion, if we need to.
4086  if (SCS1.First == ICK_Array_To_Pointer)
4087  FromType1 = S.Context.getArrayDecayedType(FromType1);
4088  if (SCS2.First == ICK_Array_To_Pointer)
4089  FromType2 = S.Context.getArrayDecayedType(FromType2);
4090 
4091  QualType FromPointee1 = FromType1->getPointeeType().getUnqualifiedType();
4092  QualType FromPointee2 = FromType2->getPointeeType().getUnqualifiedType();
4093 
4094  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromPointee2, FromPointee1))
4095  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4096  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromPointee1, FromPointee2))
4097  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4098 
4099  // Objective-C++: If one interface is more specific than the
4100  // other, it is the better one.
4101  const ObjCObjectPointerType* FromObjCPtr1
4102  = FromType1->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
4103  const ObjCObjectPointerType* FromObjCPtr2
4104  = FromType2->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
4105  if (FromObjCPtr1 && FromObjCPtr2) {
4106  bool AssignLeft = S.Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(FromObjCPtr1,
4107  FromObjCPtr2);
4108  bool AssignRight = S.Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(FromObjCPtr2,
4109  FromObjCPtr1);
4110  if (AssignLeft != AssignRight) {
4111  return AssignLeft? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4112  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4113  }
4114  }
4115  }
4116 
4117  if (SCS1.ReferenceBinding && SCS2.ReferenceBinding) {
4118  // Check for a better reference binding based on the kind of bindings.
4119  if (isBetterReferenceBindingKind(SCS1, SCS2))
4120  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4121  else if (isBetterReferenceBindingKind(SCS2, SCS1))
4122  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4123  }
4124 
4125  // Compare based on qualification conversions (C++ 13.3.3.2p3,
4126  // bullet 3).
4127  if (ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind QualCK
4128  = CompareQualificationConversions(S, SCS1, SCS2))
4129  return QualCK;
4130 
4131  if (SCS1.ReferenceBinding && SCS2.ReferenceBinding) {
4132  // C++ [over.ics.rank]p3b4:
4133  // -- S1 and S2 are reference bindings (8.5.3), and the types to
4134  // which the references refer are the same type except for
4135  // top-level cv-qualifiers, and the type to which the reference
4136  // initialized by S2 refers is more cv-qualified than the type
4137  // to which the reference initialized by S1 refers.
4138  QualType T1 = SCS1.getToType(2);
4139  QualType T2 = SCS2.getToType(2);
4140  T1 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(T1);
4141  T2 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(T2);
4142  Qualifiers T1Quals, T2Quals;
4143  QualType UnqualT1 = S.Context.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T1, T1Quals);
4144  QualType UnqualT2 = S.Context.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T2, T2Quals);
4145  if (UnqualT1 == UnqualT2) {
4146  // Objective-C++ ARC: If the references refer to objects with different
4147  // lifetimes, prefer bindings that don't change lifetime.
4148  if (SCS1.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding !=
4149  SCS2.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding) {
4150  return SCS1.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding
4151  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse
4152  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4153  }
4154 
4155  // If the type is an array type, promote the element qualifiers to the
4156  // type for comparison.
4157  if (isa<ArrayType>(T1) && T1Quals)
4158  T1 = S.Context.getQualifiedType(UnqualT1, T1Quals);
4159  if (isa<ArrayType>(T2) && T2Quals)
4160  T2 = S.Context.getQualifiedType(UnqualT2, T2Quals);
4161  if (T2.isMoreQualifiedThan(T1))
4162  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4163  if (T1.isMoreQualifiedThan(T2))
4164  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4165  }
4166  }
4167 
4168  // In Microsoft mode (below 19.28), prefer an integral conversion to a
4169  // floating-to-integral conversion if the integral conversion
4170  // is between types of the same size.
4171  // For example:
4172  // void f(float);
4173  // void f(int);
4174  // int main {
4175  // long a;
4176  // f(a);
4177  // }
4178  // Here, MSVC will call f(int) instead of generating a compile error
4179  // as clang will do in standard mode.
4180  if (S.getLangOpts().MSVCCompat &&
4181  !S.getLangOpts().isCompatibleWithMSVC(LangOptions::MSVC2019_8) &&
4182  SCS1.Second == ICK_Integral_Conversion &&
4183  SCS2.Second == ICK_Floating_Integral &&
4184  S.Context.getTypeSize(SCS1.getFromType()) ==
4185  S.Context.getTypeSize(SCS1.getToType(2)))
4186  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4187 
4188  // Prefer a compatible vector conversion over a lax vector conversion
4189  // For example:
4190  //
4191  // typedef float __v4sf __attribute__((__vector_size__(16)));
4192  // void f(vector float);
4193  // void f(vector signed int);
4194  // int main() {
4195  // __v4sf a;
4196  // f(a);
4197  // }
4198  // Here, we'd like to choose f(vector float) and not
4199  // report an ambiguous call error
4200  if (SCS1.Second == ICK_Vector_Conversion &&
4201  SCS2.Second == ICK_Vector_Conversion) {
4202  bool SCS1IsCompatibleVectorConversion = S.Context.areCompatibleVectorTypes(
4203  SCS1.getFromType(), SCS1.getToType(2));
4204  bool SCS2IsCompatibleVectorConversion = S.Context.areCompatibleVectorTypes(
4205  SCS2.getFromType(), SCS2.getToType(2));
4206 
4207  if (SCS1IsCompatibleVectorConversion != SCS2IsCompatibleVectorConversion)
4208  return SCS1IsCompatibleVectorConversion
4209  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4210  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4211  }
4212 
4213  if (SCS1.Second == ICK_SVE_Vector_Conversion &&
4214  SCS2.Second == ICK_SVE_Vector_Conversion) {
4215  bool SCS1IsCompatibleSVEVectorConversion =
4216  S.Context.areCompatibleSveTypes(SCS1.getFromType(), SCS1.getToType(2));
4217  bool SCS2IsCompatibleSVEVectorConversion =
4218  S.Context.areCompatibleSveTypes(SCS2.getFromType(), SCS2.getToType(2));
4219 
4220  if (SCS1IsCompatibleSVEVectorConversion !=
4221  SCS2IsCompatibleSVEVectorConversion)
4222  return SCS1IsCompatibleSVEVectorConversion
4223  ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4224  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4225  }
4226 
4227  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
4228 }
4229 
4230 /// CompareQualificationConversions - Compares two standard conversion
4231 /// sequences to determine whether they can be ranked based on their
4232 /// qualification conversions (C++ 13.3.3.2p3 bullet 3).
4233 static ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind
4234 CompareQualificationConversions(Sema &S,
4235  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS1,
4236  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS2) {
4237  // C++ [over.ics.rank]p3:
4238  // -- S1 and S2 differ only in their qualification conversion and
4239  // yield similar types T1 and T2 (C++ 4.4), respectively, [...]
4240  // [C++98]
4241  // [...] and the cv-qualification signature of type T1 is a proper subset
4242  // of the cv-qualification signature of type T2, and S1 is not the
4243  // deprecated string literal array-to-pointer conversion (4.2).
4244  // [C++2a]
4245  // [...] where T1 can be converted to T2 by a qualification conversion.
4246  if (SCS1.First != SCS2.First || SCS1.Second != SCS2.Second ||
4247  SCS1.Third != SCS2.Third || SCS1.Third != ICK_Qualification)
4248  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
4249 
4250  // FIXME: the example in the standard doesn't use a qualification
4251  // conversion (!)
4252  QualType T1 = SCS1.getToType(2);
4253  QualType T2 = SCS2.getToType(2);
4254  T1 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(T1);
4255  T2 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(T2);
4256  assert(!T1->isReferenceType() && !T2->isReferenceType());
4257  Qualifiers T1Quals, T2Quals;
4258  QualType UnqualT1 = S.Context.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T1, T1Quals);
4259  QualType UnqualT2 = S.Context.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T2, T2Quals);
4260 
4261  // If the types are the same, we won't learn anything by unwrapping
4262  // them.
4263  if (UnqualT1 == UnqualT2)
4264  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
4265 
4266  // Don't ever prefer a standard conversion sequence that uses the deprecated
4267  // string literal array to pointer conversion.
4268  bool CanPick1 = !SCS1.DeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtr;
4269  bool CanPick2 = !SCS2.DeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtr;
4270 
4271  // Objective-C++ ARC:
4272  // Prefer qualification conversions not involving a change in lifetime
4273  // to qualification conversions that do change lifetime.
4274  if (SCS1.QualificationIncludesObjCLifetime &&
4275  !SCS2.QualificationIncludesObjCLifetime)
4276  CanPick1 = false;
4277  if (SCS2.QualificationIncludesObjCLifetime &&
4278  !SCS1.QualificationIncludesObjCLifetime)
4279  CanPick2 = false;
4280 
4281  bool ObjCLifetimeConversion;
4282  if (CanPick1 &&
4283  !S.IsQualificationConversion(T1, T2, false, ObjCLifetimeConversion))
4284  CanPick1 = false;
4285  // FIXME: In Objective-C ARC, we can have qualification conversions in both
4286  // directions, so we can't short-cut this second check in general.
4287  if (CanPick2 &&
4288  !S.IsQualificationConversion(T2, T1, false, ObjCLifetimeConversion))
4289  CanPick2 = false;
4290 
4291  if (CanPick1 != CanPick2)
4292  return CanPick1 ? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4293  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4294  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
4295 }
4296 
4297 /// CompareDerivedToBaseConversions - Compares two standard conversion
4298 /// sequences to determine whether they can be ranked based on their
4299 /// various kinds of derived-to-base conversions (C++
4300 /// [over.ics.rank]p4b3). As part of these checks, we also look at
4301 /// conversions between Objective-C interface types.
4302 static ImplicitConversionSequence::CompareKind
4303 CompareDerivedToBaseConversions(Sema &S, SourceLocation Loc,
4304  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS1,
4305  const StandardConversionSequence& SCS2) {
4306  QualType FromType1 = SCS1.getFromType();
4307  QualType ToType1 = SCS1.getToType(1);
4308  QualType FromType2 = SCS2.getFromType();
4309  QualType ToType2 = SCS2.getToType(1);
4310 
4311  // Adjust the types we're converting from via the array-to-pointer
4312  // conversion, if we need to.
4313  if (SCS1.First == ICK_Array_To_Pointer)
4314  FromType1 = S.Context.getArrayDecayedType(FromType1);
4315  if (SCS2.First == ICK_Array_To_Pointer)
4316  FromType2 = S.Context.getArrayDecayedType(FromType2);
4317 
4318  // Canonicalize all of the types.
4319  FromType1 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(FromType1);
4320  ToType1 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(ToType1);
4321  FromType2 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(FromType2);
4322  ToType2 = S.Context.getCanonicalType(ToType2);
4323 
4324  // C++ [over.ics.rank]p4b3:
4325  //
4326  // If class B is derived directly or indirectly from class A and
4327  // class C is derived directly or indirectly from B,
4328  //
4329  // Compare based on pointer conversions.
4330  if (SCS1.Second == ICK_Pointer_Conversion &&
4331  SCS2.Second == ICK_Pointer_Conversion &&
4332  /*FIXME: Remove if Objective-C id conversions get their own rank*/
4333  FromType1->isPointerType() && FromType2->isPointerType() &&
4334  ToType1->isPointerType() && ToType2->isPointerType()) {
4335  QualType FromPointee1 =
4336  FromType1->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType().getUnqualifiedType();
4337  QualType ToPointee1 =
4338  ToType1->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType().getUnqualifiedType();
4339  QualType FromPointee2 =
4340  FromType2->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType().getUnqualifiedType();
4341  QualType ToPointee2 =
4342  ToType2->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType().getUnqualifiedType();
4343 
4344  // -- conversion of C* to B* is better than conversion of C* to A*,
4345  if (FromPointee1 == FromPointee2 && ToPointee1 != ToPointee2) {
4346  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, ToPointee1, ToPointee2))
4347  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4348  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, ToPointee2, ToPointee1))
4349  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4350  }
4351 
4352  // -- conversion of B* to A* is better than conversion of C* to A*,
4353  if (FromPointee1 != FromPointee2 && ToPointee1 == ToPointee2) {
4354  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromPointee2, FromPointee1))
4355  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4356  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromPointee1, FromPointee2))
4357  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4358  }
4359  } else if (SCS1.Second == ICK_Pointer_Conversion &&
4360  SCS2.Second == ICK_Pointer_Conversion) {
4361  const ObjCObjectPointerType *FromPtr1
4362  = FromType1->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
4363  const ObjCObjectPointerType *FromPtr2
4364  = FromType2->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
4365  const ObjCObjectPointerType *ToPtr1
4366  = ToType1->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
4367  const ObjCObjectPointerType *ToPtr2
4368  = ToType2->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
4369 
4370  if (FromPtr1 && FromPtr2 && ToPtr1 && ToPtr2) {
4371  // Apply the same conversion ranking rules for Objective-C pointer types
4372  // that we do for C++ pointers to class types. However, we employ the
4373  // Objective-C pseudo-subtyping relationship used for assignment of
4374  // Objective-C pointer types.
4375  bool FromAssignLeft
4376  = S.Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(FromPtr1, FromPtr2);
4377  bool FromAssignRight
4378  = S.Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(FromPtr2, FromPtr1);
4379  bool ToAssignLeft
4380  = S.Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(ToPtr1, ToPtr2);
4381  bool ToAssignRight
4382  = S.Context.canAssignObjCInterfaces(ToPtr2, ToPtr1);
4383 
4384  // A conversion to an a non-id object pointer type or qualified 'id'
4385  // type is better than a conversion to 'id'.
4386  if (ToPtr1->isObjCIdType() &&
4387  (ToPtr2->isObjCQualifiedIdType() || ToPtr2->getInterfaceDecl()))
4388  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4389  if (ToPtr2->isObjCIdType() &&
4390  (ToPtr1->isObjCQualifiedIdType() || ToPtr1->getInterfaceDecl()))
4391  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4392 
4393  // A conversion to a non-id object pointer type is better than a
4394  // conversion to a qualified 'id' type
4395  if (ToPtr1->isObjCQualifiedIdType() && ToPtr2->getInterfaceDecl())
4396  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4397  if (ToPtr2->isObjCQualifiedIdType() && ToPtr1->getInterfaceDecl())
4398  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4399 
4400  // A conversion to an a non-Class object pointer type or qualified 'Class'
4401  // type is better than a conversion to 'Class'.
4402  if (ToPtr1->isObjCClassType() &&
4403  (ToPtr2->isObjCQualifiedClassType() || ToPtr2->getInterfaceDecl()))
4404  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4405  if (ToPtr2->isObjCClassType() &&
4406  (ToPtr1->isObjCQualifiedClassType() || ToPtr1->getInterfaceDecl()))
4407  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4408 
4409  // A conversion to a non-Class object pointer type is better than a
4410  // conversion to a qualified 'Class' type.
4411  if (ToPtr1->isObjCQualifiedClassType() && ToPtr2->getInterfaceDecl())
4412  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4413  if (ToPtr2->isObjCQualifiedClassType() && ToPtr1->getInterfaceDecl())
4414  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4415 
4416  // -- "conversion of C* to B* is better than conversion of C* to A*,"
4417  if (S.Context.hasSameType(FromType1, FromType2) &&
4418  !FromPtr1->isObjCIdType() && !FromPtr1->isObjCClassType() &&
4419  (ToAssignLeft != ToAssignRight)) {
4420  if (FromPtr1->isSpecialized()) {
4421  // "conversion of B<A> * to B * is better than conversion of B * to
4422  // C *.
4423  bool IsFirstSame =
4424  FromPtr1->getInterfaceDecl() == ToPtr1->getInterfaceDecl();
4425  bool IsSecondSame =
4426  FromPtr1->getInterfaceDecl() == ToPtr2->getInterfaceDecl();
4427  if (IsFirstSame) {
4428  if (!IsSecondSame)
4429  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4430  } else if (IsSecondSame)
4431  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4432  }
4433  return ToAssignLeft? ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse
4434  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4435  }
4436 
4437  // -- "conversion of B* to A* is better than conversion of C* to A*,"
4438  if (S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ToType1, ToType2) &&
4439  (FromAssignLeft != FromAssignRight))
4440  return FromAssignLeft? ImplicitConversionSequence::Better
4441  : ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4442  }
4443  }
4444 
4445  // Ranking of member-pointer types.
4446  if (SCS1.Second == ICK_Pointer_Member && SCS2.Second == ICK_Pointer_Member &&
4447  FromType1->isMemberPointerType() && FromType2->isMemberPointerType() &&
4448  ToType1->isMemberPointerType() && ToType2->isMemberPointerType()) {
4449  const auto *FromMemPointer1 = FromType1->castAs<MemberPointerType>();
4450  const auto *ToMemPointer1 = ToType1->castAs<MemberPointerType>();
4451  const auto *FromMemPointer2 = FromType2->castAs<MemberPointerType>();
4452  const auto *ToMemPointer2 = ToType2->castAs<MemberPointerType>();
4453  const Type *FromPointeeType1 = FromMemPointer1->getClass();
4454  const Type *ToPointeeType1 = ToMemPointer1->getClass();
4455  const Type *FromPointeeType2 = FromMemPointer2->getClass();
4456  const Type *ToPointeeType2 = ToMemPointer2->getClass();
4457  QualType FromPointee1 = QualType(FromPointeeType1, 0).getUnqualifiedType();
4458  QualType ToPointee1 = QualType(ToPointeeType1, 0).getUnqualifiedType();
4459  QualType FromPointee2 = QualType(FromPointeeType2, 0).getUnqualifiedType();
4460  QualType ToPointee2 = QualType(ToPointeeType2, 0).getUnqualifiedType();
4461  // conversion of A::* to B::* is better than conversion of A::* to C::*,
4462  if (FromPointee1 == FromPointee2 && ToPointee1 != ToPointee2) {
4463  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, ToPointee1, ToPointee2))
4464  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4465  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, ToPointee2, ToPointee1))
4466  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4467  }
4468  // conversion of B::* to C::* is better than conversion of A::* to C::*
4469  if (ToPointee1 == ToPointee2 && FromPointee1 != FromPointee2) {
4470  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromPointee1, FromPointee2))
4471  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4472  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromPointee2, FromPointee1))
4473  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4474  }
4475  }
4476 
4477  if (SCS1.Second == ICK_Derived_To_Base) {
4478  // -- conversion of C to B is better than conversion of C to A,
4479  // -- binding of an expression of type C to a reference of type
4480  // B& is better than binding an expression of type C to a
4481  // reference of type A&,
4482  if (S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromType1, FromType2) &&
4483  !S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ToType1, ToType2)) {
4484  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, ToType1, ToType2))
4485  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4486  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, ToType2, ToType1))
4487  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4488  }
4489 
4490  // -- conversion of B to A is better than conversion of C to A.
4491  // -- binding of an expression of type B to a reference of type
4492  // A& is better than binding an expression of type C to a
4493  // reference of type A&,
4494  if (!S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(FromType1, FromType2) &&
4495  S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(ToType1, ToType2)) {
4496  if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromType2, FromType1))
4497  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Better;
4498  else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromType1, FromType2))
4499  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse;
4500  }
4501  }
4502 
4503  return ImplicitConversionSequence::Indistinguishable;
4504 }
4505 
4506 /// Determine whether the given type is valid, e.g., it is not an invalid
4507 /// C++ class.
4508 static bool isTypeValid(QualType T) {
4509  if (CXXRecordDecl *Record = T->getAsCXXRecordDecl())
4510  return !Record->isInvalidDecl();
4511 
4512  return true;
4513 }
4514 
4515 static QualType withoutUnaligned(ASTContext &Ctx, QualType T) {
4516  if (!T.getQualifiers().hasUnaligned())
4517  return T;
4518 
4519  Qualifiers Q;
4520  T = Ctx.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T, Q);
4521  Q.removeUnaligned();
4522  return Ctx.getQualifiedType(T, Q);
4523 }
4524 
4525 /// CompareReferenceRelationship - Compare the two types T1 and T2 to
4526 /// determine whether they are reference-compatible,
4527 /// reference-related, or incompatible, for use in C++ initialization by
4528 /// reference (C++ [dcl.ref.init]p4). Neither type can be a reference
4529 /// type, and the first type (T1) is the pointee type of the reference
4530 /// type being initialized.
4531 Sema::ReferenceCompareResult
4532 Sema::CompareReferenceRelationship(SourceLocation Loc,
4533  QualType OrigT1, QualType OrigT2,
4534  ReferenceConversions *ConvOut) {
4535  assert(!OrigT1->isReferenceType() &&
4536  "T1 must be the pointee type of the reference type");
4537  assert(!OrigT2->isReferenceType() && "T2 cannot be a reference type");
4538 
4539  QualType T1 = Context.getCanonicalType(OrigT1);
4540  QualType T2 = Context.getCanonicalType(OrigT2);
4541  Qualifiers T1Quals, T2Quals;
4542  QualType UnqualT1 = Context.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T1, T1Quals);
4543  QualType UnqualT2 = Context.getUnqualifiedArrayType(T2, T2Quals);
4544 
4545  ReferenceConversions ConvTmp;
4546  ReferenceConversions &Conv = ConvOut ? *ConvOut : ConvTmp;
4547  Conv = ReferenceConversions();
4548 
4549  // C++2a [dcl.init.ref]p4:
4550  // Given types "cv1 T1" and "cv2 T2," "cv1 T1" is
4551  // reference-related to "cv2 T2" if T1 is similar to T2, or
4552  // T1 is a base class of T2.
4553  // "cv1 T1" is reference-compatible with "cv2 T2" if
4554  // a prvalue of type "pointer to cv2 T2" can be converted to the type
4555  // "pointer to cv1 T1" via a standard conversion sequence.
4556 
4557  // Check for standard conversions we can apply to pointers: derived-to-base
4558  // conversions, ObjC pointer conversions, and function pointer conversions.
4559  // (Qualification conversions are checked last.)
4560  QualType ConvertedT2;
4561  if (UnqualT1 == UnqualT2) {
4562  // Nothing to do.
4563  } else if (isCompleteType(Loc, OrigT2) &&
4564  isTypeValid(UnqualT1) && isTypeValid(UnqualT2) &&
4565  IsDerivedFrom(Loc, UnqualT2, UnqualT1))
4566  Conv |= ReferenceConversions::DerivedToBase;
4567  else if (UnqualT1->isObjCObjectOrInterfaceType() &&
4568  UnqualT2->isObjCObjectOrInterfaceType() &&
4569  Context.canBindObjCObjectType(UnqualT1, UnqualT2))
4570  Conv |= ReferenceConversions::ObjC;
4571  else if (UnqualT2->isFunctionType() &&
4572  IsFunctionConversion(UnqualT2, UnqualT1, ConvertedT2)) {
4573  Conv |= ReferenceConversions::Function;
4574  // No need to check qualifiers; function types don't have them.
4575  return Ref_Compatible;
4576  }
4577  bool ConvertedReferent = Conv != 0;
4578 
4579  // We can have a qualification conversion. Compute whether the types are
4580  // similar at the same time.
4581  bool PreviousToQualsIncludeConst = true;
4582  bool TopLevel = true;
4583  do {
4584  if (T1 == T2)
4585  break;
4586 
4587  // We will need a qualification conversion.
4588  Conv |= ReferenceConversions::Qualification;
4589 
4590  // Track whether we performed a qualification conversion anywhere other
4591  // than the top level. This matters for ranking reference bindings in
4592  // overload resolution.
4593  if (!TopLevel)
4594  Conv |= ReferenceConversions::NestedQualification;
4595 
4596  // MS compiler ignores __unaligned qualifier for references; do the same.
4597  T1 = withoutUnaligned(Context, T1);
4598  T2 = withoutUnaligned(Context, T2);
4599 
4600  // If we find a qualifier mismatch, the types are not reference-compatible,
4601  // but are still be reference-related if they're similar.
4602  bool ObjCLifetimeConversion = false;
4603  if (!isQualificationConversionStep(T2, T1, /*CStyle=*/false, TopLevel,
4604  PreviousToQualsIncludeConst,
4605  ObjCLifetimeConversion))
4606  return (ConvertedReferent || Context.hasSimilarType(T1, T2))
4607  ? Ref_Related
4608  : Ref_Incompatible;
4609 
4610  // FIXME: Should we track this for any level other than the first?
4611  if (ObjCLifetimeConversion)
4612  Conv |= ReferenceConversions::ObjCLifetime;
4613 
4614  TopLevel = false;
4615  } while (Context.UnwrapSimilarTypes(T1, T2));
4616 
4617  // At this point, if the types are reference-related, we must either have the
4618  // same inner type (ignoring qualifiers), or must have already worked out how
4619  // to convert the referent.
4620  return (ConvertedReferent || Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(T1, T2))
4621  ? Ref_Compatible
4622  : Ref_Incompatible;
4623 }
4624 
4625 /// Look for a user-defined conversion to a value reference-compatible
4626 /// with DeclType. Return true if something definite is found.
4627 static bool
4628 FindConversionForRefInit(Sema &S, ImplicitConversionSequence &ICS,
4629  QualType DeclType, SourceLocation DeclLoc,
4630  Expr *Init, QualType T2, bool AllowRvalues,
4631  bool AllowExplicit) {
4632  assert(T2->isRecordType() && "Can only find conversions of record types.");
4633  auto *T2RecordDecl = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(T2->castAs<RecordType>()->getDecl());
4634 
4635  OverloadCandidateSet CandidateSet(
4636  DeclLoc, OverloadCandidateSet::CSK_InitByUserDefinedConversion);
4637  const auto &Conversions = T2RecordDecl->getVisibleConversionFunctions();
4638  for (auto I = Conversions.begin(), E = Conversions.end(); I != E; ++I) {
4639  NamedDecl *D = *I;
4640  CXXRecordDecl *ActingDC = cast<CXXRecordDecl>(D->getDeclContext());
4641  if (isa<UsingShadowDecl>(D))
4642  D = cast<UsingShadowDecl>(D)->getTargetDecl();
4643 
4644  FunctionTemplateDecl *ConvTemplate
4645  = dyn_cast<FunctionTemplateDecl>(D);
4646  CXXConversionDecl *Conv;
4647  if (ConvTemplate)
4648  Conv = cast<CXXConversionDecl>(ConvTemplate->getTemplatedDecl());
4649  else
4650  Conv = cast<CXXConversionDecl>(D);
4651 
4652  if (AllowRvalues) {
4653  // If we are initializing an rvalue reference, don't permit conversion
4654  // functions that return lvalues.
4655  if (!ConvTemplate && DeclType->isRValueReferenceType()) {
4656  const ReferenceType *RefType
4657  = Conv->getConversionType()->getAs<LValueReferenceType>();
4658  if (RefType && !RefType->getPointeeType()->isFunctionType())
4659  continue;
4660  }
4661 
4662  if (!ConvTemplate &&
4663  S.CompareReferenceRelationship(
4664  DeclLoc,
4665  Conv->getConversionType()
4666  .getNonReferenceType()
4667  .getUnqualifiedType(),
4668  DeclType.getNonReferenceType().getUnqualifiedType()) ==
4669  Sema::Ref_Incompatible)
4670  continue;
4671  } else {
4672  // If the conversion function doesn't return a reference type,
4673  // it can't be considered for this conversion. An rvalue reference
4674  // is only acceptable if its referencee is a function type.
4675 
4676  const ReferenceType *RefType =
4677  Conv->getConversionType()->getAs<ReferenceType>();
4678  if (!RefType ||
4679  (!RefType->isLValueReferenceType() &&
4680  !RefType->getPointeeType()->isFunctionType()))
4681  continue;
4682  }
4683 
4684  if (ConvTemplate)
4685  S.AddTemplateConversionCandidate(
4686  ConvTemplate, I.getPair(), ActingDC, Init, DeclType, CandidateSet,
4687  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/false, AllowExplicit);
4688  else
4689  S.AddConversionCandidate(
4690  Conv, I.getPair(), ActingDC, Init, DeclType, CandidateSet,
4691  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/false, AllowExplicit);
4692  }
4693 
4694  bool HadMultipleCandidates = (CandidateSet.size() > 1);
4695 
4696  OverloadCandidateSet::iterator Best;
4697  switch (CandidateSet.BestViableFunction(S, DeclLoc, Best)) {
4698  case OR_Success:
4699  // C++ [over.ics.ref]p1:
4700  //
4701  // [...] If the parameter binds directly to the result of
4702  // applying a conversion function to the argument
4703  // expression, the implicit conversion sequence is a
4704  // user-defined conversion sequence (13.3.3.1.2), with the
4705  // second standard conversion sequence either an identity
4706  // conversion or, if the conversion function returns an
4707  // entity of a type that is a derived class of the parameter
4708  // type, a derived-to-base Conversion.
4709  if (!Best->FinalConversion.DirectBinding)
4710  return false;
4711 
4712  ICS.setUserDefined();
4713  ICS.UserDefined.Before = Best->Conversions[0].Standard;
4714  ICS.UserDefined.After = Best->FinalConversion;
4715  ICS.UserDefined.HadMultipleCandidates = HadMultipleCandidates;
4716  ICS.UserDefined.ConversionFunction = Best->Function;
4717  ICS.UserDefined.FoundConversionFunction = Best->FoundDecl;
4718  ICS.UserDefined.EllipsisConversion = false;
4719  assert(ICS.UserDefined.After.ReferenceBinding &&
4720  ICS.UserDefined.After.DirectBinding &&
4721  "Expected a direct reference binding!");
4722  return true;
4723 
4724  case OR_Ambiguous:
4725  ICS.setAmbiguous();
4726  for (OverloadCandidateSet::iterator Cand = CandidateSet.begin();
4727  Cand != CandidateSet.end(); ++Cand)
4728  if (Cand->Best)
4729  ICS.Ambiguous.addConversion(Cand->FoundDecl, Cand->Function);
4730  return true;
4731 
4732  case OR_No_Viable_Function:
4733  case OR_Deleted:
4734  // There was no suitable conversion, or we found a deleted
4735  // conversion; continue with other checks.
4736  return false;
4737  }
4738 
4739  llvm_unreachable("Invalid OverloadResult!");
4740 }
4741 
4742 /// Compute an implicit conversion sequence for reference
4743 /// initialization.
4744 static ImplicitConversionSequence
4745 TryReferenceInit(Sema &S, Expr *Init, QualType DeclType,
4746  SourceLocation DeclLoc,
4747  bool SuppressUserConversions,
4748  bool AllowExplicit) {
4749  assert(DeclType->isReferenceType() && "Reference init needs a reference");
4750 
4751  // Most paths end in a failed conversion.
4752  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS;
4753  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::no_conversion, Init, DeclType);
4754 
4755  QualType T1 = DeclType->castAs<ReferenceType>()->getPointeeType();
4756  QualType T2 = Init->getType();
4757 
4758  // If the initializer is the address of an overloaded function, try
4759  // to resolve the overloaded function. If all goes well, T2 is the
4760  // type of the resulting function.
4761  if (S.Context.getCanonicalType(T2) == S.Context.OverloadTy) {
4762  DeclAccessPair Found;
4763  if (FunctionDecl *Fn = S.ResolveAddressOfOverloadedFunction(Init, DeclType,
4764  false, Found))
4765  T2 = Fn->getType();
4766  }
4767 
4768  // Compute some basic properties of the types and the initializer.
4769  bool isRValRef = DeclType->isRValueReferenceType();
4770  Expr::Classification InitCategory = Init->Classify(S.Context);
4771 
4772  Sema::ReferenceConversions RefConv;
4773  Sema::ReferenceCompareResult RefRelationship =
4774  S.CompareReferenceRelationship(DeclLoc, T1, T2, &RefConv);
4775 
4776  auto SetAsReferenceBinding = [&](bool BindsDirectly) {
4777  ICS.setStandard();
4778  ICS.Standard.First = ICK_Identity;
4779  // FIXME: A reference binding can be a function conversion too. We should
4780  // consider that when ordering reference-to-function bindings.
4781  ICS.Standard.Second = (RefConv & Sema::ReferenceConversions::DerivedToBase)
4782  ? ICK_Derived_To_Base
4783  : (RefConv & Sema::ReferenceConversions::ObjC)
4784  ? ICK_Compatible_Conversion
4785  : ICK_Identity;
4786  // FIXME: As a speculative fix to a defect introduced by CWG2352, we rank
4787  // a reference binding that performs a non-top-level qualification
4788  // conversion as a qualification conversion, not as an identity conversion.
4789  ICS.Standard.Third = (RefConv &
4790  Sema::ReferenceConversions::NestedQualification)
4791  ? ICK_Qualification
4792  : ICK_Identity;
4793  ICS.Standard.setFromType(T2);
4794  ICS.Standard.setToType(0, T2);
4795  ICS.Standard.setToType(1, T1);
4796  ICS.Standard.setToType(2, T1);
4797  ICS.Standard.ReferenceBinding = true;
4798  ICS.Standard.DirectBinding = BindsDirectly;
4799  ICS.Standard.IsLvalueReference = !isRValRef;
4800  ICS.Standard.BindsToFunctionLvalue = T2->isFunctionType();
4801  ICS.Standard.BindsToRvalue = InitCategory.isRValue();
4802  ICS.Standard.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier = false;
4803  ICS.Standard.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding =
4804  (RefConv & Sema::ReferenceConversions::ObjCLifetime) != 0;
4805  ICS.Standard.CopyConstructor = nullptr;
4806  ICS.Standard.DeprecatedStringLiteralToCharPtr = false;
4807  };
4808 
4809  // C++0x [dcl.init.ref]p5:
4810  // A reference to type "cv1 T1" is initialized by an expression
4811  // of type "cv2 T2" as follows:
4812 
4813  // -- If reference is an lvalue reference and the initializer expression
4814  if (!isRValRef) {
4815  // -- is an lvalue (but is not a bit-field), and "cv1 T1" is
4816  // reference-compatible with "cv2 T2," or
4817  //
4818  // Per C++ [over.ics.ref]p4, we don't check the bit-field property here.
4819  if (InitCategory.isLValue() && RefRelationship == Sema::Ref_Compatible) {
4820  // C++ [over.ics.ref]p1:
4821  // When a parameter of reference type binds directly (8.5.3)
4822  // to an argument expression, the implicit conversion sequence
4823  // is the identity conversion, unless the argument expression
4824  // has a type that is a derived class of the parameter type,
4825  // in which case the implicit conversion sequence is a
4826  // derived-to-base Conversion (13.3.3.1).
4827  SetAsReferenceBinding(/*BindsDirectly=*/true);
4828 
4829  // Nothing more to do: the inaccessibility/ambiguity check for
4830  // derived-to-base conversions is suppressed when we're
4831  // computing the implicit conversion sequence (C++
4832  // [over.best.ics]p2).
4833  return ICS;
4834  }
4835 
4836  // -- has a class type (i.e., T2 is a class type), where T1 is
4837  // not reference-related to T2, and can be implicitly
4838  // converted to an lvalue of type "cv3 T3," where "cv1 T1"
4839  // is reference-compatible with "cv3 T3" 92) (this
4840  // conversion is selected by enumerating the applicable
4841  // conversion functions (13.3.1.6) and choosing the best
4842  // one through overload resolution (13.3)),
4843  if (!SuppressUserConversions && T2->isRecordType() &&
4844  S.isCompleteType(DeclLoc, T2) &&
4845  RefRelationship == Sema::Ref_Incompatible) {
4846  if (FindConversionForRefInit(S, ICS, DeclType, DeclLoc,
4847  Init, T2, /*AllowRvalues=*/false,
4848  AllowExplicit))
4849  return ICS;
4850  }
4851  }
4852 
4853  // -- Otherwise, the reference shall be an lvalue reference to a
4854  // non-volatile const type (i.e., cv1 shall be const), or the reference
4855  // shall be an rvalue reference.
4856  if (!isRValRef && (!T1.isConstQualified() || T1.isVolatileQualified())) {
4857  if (InitCategory.isRValue() && RefRelationship != Sema::Ref_Incompatible)
4858  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::lvalue_ref_to_rvalue, Init, DeclType);
4859  return ICS;
4860  }
4861 
4862  // -- If the initializer expression
4863  //
4864  // -- is an xvalue, class prvalue, array prvalue or function
4865  // lvalue and "cv1 T1" is reference-compatible with "cv2 T2", or
4866  if (RefRelationship == Sema::Ref_Compatible &&
4867  (InitCategory.isXValue() ||
4868  (InitCategory.isPRValue() &&
4869  (T2->isRecordType() || T2->isArrayType())) ||
4870  (InitCategory.isLValue() && T2->isFunctionType()))) {
4871  // In C++11, this is always a direct binding. In C++98/03, it's a direct
4872  // binding unless we're binding to a class prvalue.
4873  // Note: Although xvalues wouldn't normally show up in C++98/03 code, we
4874  // allow the use of rvalue references in C++98/03 for the benefit of
4875  // standard library implementors; therefore, we need the xvalue check here.
4876  SetAsReferenceBinding(/*BindsDirectly=*/S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 ||
4877  !(InitCategory.isPRValue() || T2->isRecordType()));
4878  return ICS;
4879  }
4880 
4881  // -- has a class type (i.e., T2 is a class type), where T1 is not
4882  // reference-related to T2, and can be implicitly converted to
4883  // an xvalue, class prvalue, or function lvalue of type
4884  // "cv3 T3", where "cv1 T1" is reference-compatible with
4885  // "cv3 T3",
4886  //
4887  // then the reference is bound to the value of the initializer
4888  // expression in the first case and to the result of the conversion
4889  // in the second case (or, in either case, to an appropriate base
4890  // class subobject).
4891  if (!SuppressUserConversions && RefRelationship == Sema::Ref_Incompatible &&
4892  T2->isRecordType() && S.isCompleteType(DeclLoc, T2) &&
4893  FindConversionForRefInit(S, ICS, DeclType, DeclLoc,
4894  Init, T2, /*AllowRvalues=*/true,
4895  AllowExplicit)) {
4896  // In the second case, if the reference is an rvalue reference
4897  // and the second standard conversion sequence of the
4898  // user-defined conversion sequence includes an lvalue-to-rvalue
4899  // conversion, the program is ill-formed.
4900  if (ICS.isUserDefined() && isRValRef &&
4901  ICS.UserDefined.After.First == ICK_Lvalue_To_Rvalue)
4902  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::no_conversion, Init, DeclType);
4903 
4904  return ICS;
4905  }
4906 
4907  // A temporary of function type cannot be created; don't even try.
4908  if (T1->isFunctionType())
4909  return ICS;
4910 
4911  // -- Otherwise, a temporary of type "cv1 T1" is created and
4912  // initialized from the initializer expression using the
4913  // rules for a non-reference copy initialization (8.5). The
4914  // reference is then bound to the temporary. If T1 is
4915  // reference-related to T2, cv1 must be the same
4916  // cv-qualification as, or greater cv-qualification than,
4917  // cv2; otherwise, the program is ill-formed.
4918  if (RefRelationship == Sema::Ref_Related) {
4919  // If cv1 == cv2 or cv1 is a greater cv-qualified than cv2, then
4920  // we would be reference-compatible or reference-compatible with
4921  // added qualification. But that wasn't the case, so the reference
4922  // initialization fails.
4923  //
4924  // Note that we only want to check address spaces and cvr-qualifiers here.
4925  // ObjC GC, lifetime and unaligned qualifiers aren't important.
4926  Qualifiers T1Quals = T1.getQualifiers();
4927  Qualifiers T2Quals = T2.getQualifiers();
4928  T1Quals.removeObjCGCAttr();
4929  T1Quals.removeObjCLifetime();
4930  T2Quals.removeObjCGCAttr();
4931  T2Quals.removeObjCLifetime();
4932  // MS compiler ignores __unaligned qualifier for references; do the same.
4933  T1Quals.removeUnaligned();
4934  T2Quals.removeUnaligned();
4935  if (!T1Quals.compatiblyIncludes(T2Quals))
4936  return ICS;
4937  }
4938 
4939  // If at least one of the types is a class type, the types are not
4940  // related, and we aren't allowed any user conversions, the
4941  // reference binding fails. This case is important for breaking
4942  // recursion, since TryImplicitConversion below will attempt to
4943  // create a temporary through the use of a copy constructor.
4944  if (SuppressUserConversions && RefRelationship == Sema::Ref_Incompatible &&
4945  (T1->isRecordType() || T2->isRecordType()))
4946  return ICS;
4947 
4948  // If T1 is reference-related to T2 and the reference is an rvalue
4949  // reference, the initializer expression shall not be an lvalue.
4950  if (RefRelationship >= Sema::Ref_Related && isRValRef &&
4951  Init->Classify(S.Context).isLValue()) {
4952  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::rvalue_ref_to_lvalue, Init, DeclType);
4953  return ICS;
4954  }
4955 
4956  // C++ [over.ics.ref]p2:
4957  // When a parameter of reference type is not bound directly to
4958  // an argument expression, the conversion sequence is the one
4959  // required to convert the argument expression to the
4960  // underlying type of the reference according to
4961  // 13.3.3.1. Conceptually, this conversion sequence corresponds
4962  // to copy-initializing a temporary of the underlying type with
4963  // the argument expression. Any difference in top-level
4964  // cv-qualification is subsumed by the initialization itself
4965  // and does not constitute a conversion.
4966  ICS = TryImplicitConversion(S, Init, T1, SuppressUserConversions,
4967  AllowedExplicit::None,
4968  /*InOverloadResolution=*/false,
4969  /*CStyle=*/false,
4970  /*AllowObjCWritebackConversion=*/false,
4971  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/false);
4972 
4973  // Of course, that's still a reference binding.
4974  if (ICS.isStandard()) {
4975  ICS.Standard.ReferenceBinding = true;
4976  ICS.Standard.IsLvalueReference = !isRValRef;
4977  ICS.Standard.BindsToFunctionLvalue = false;
4978  ICS.Standard.BindsToRvalue = true;
4979  ICS.Standard.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier = false;
4980  ICS.Standard.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding = false;
4981  } else if (ICS.isUserDefined()) {
4982  const ReferenceType *LValRefType =
4983  ICS.UserDefined.ConversionFunction->getReturnType()
4984  ->getAs<LValueReferenceType>();
4985 
4986  // C++ [over.ics.ref]p3:
4987  // Except for an implicit object parameter, for which see 13.3.1, a
4988  // standard conversion sequence cannot be formed if it requires [...]
4989  // binding an rvalue reference to an lvalue other than a function
4990  // lvalue.
4991  // Note that the function case is not possible here.
4992  if (isRValRef && LValRefType) {
4993  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::no_conversion, Init, DeclType);
4994  return ICS;
4995  }
4996 
4997  ICS.UserDefined.After.ReferenceBinding = true;
4998  ICS.UserDefined.After.IsLvalueReference = !isRValRef;
4999  ICS.UserDefined.After.BindsToFunctionLvalue = false;
5000  ICS.UserDefined.After.BindsToRvalue = !LValRefType;
5001  ICS.UserDefined.After.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier = false;
5002  ICS.UserDefined.After.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding = false;
5003  }
5004 
5005  return ICS;
5006 }
5007 
5008 static ImplicitConversionSequence
5009 TryCopyInitialization(Sema &S, Expr *From, QualType ToType,
5010  bool SuppressUserConversions,
5011  bool InOverloadResolution,
5012  bool AllowObjCWritebackConversion,
5013  bool AllowExplicit = false);
5014 
5015 /// TryListConversion - Try to copy-initialize a value of type ToType from the
5016 /// initializer list From.
5017 static ImplicitConversionSequence
5018 TryListConversion(Sema &S, InitListExpr *From, QualType ToType,
5019  bool SuppressUserConversions,
5020  bool InOverloadResolution,
5021  bool AllowObjCWritebackConversion) {
5022  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p1:
5023  // When an argument is an initializer list, it is not an expression and
5024  // special rules apply for converting it to a parameter type.
5025 
5026  ImplicitConversionSequence Result;
5027  Result.setBad(BadConversionSequence::no_conversion, From, ToType);
5028 
5029  // We need a complete type for what follows. With one C++20 exception,
5030  // incomplete types can never be initialized from init lists.
5031  QualType InitTy = ToType;
5032  const ArrayType *AT = S.Context.getAsArrayType(ToType);
5033  if (AT && S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus20)
5034  if (const auto *IAT = dyn_cast<IncompleteArrayType>(AT))
5035  // C++20 allows list initialization of an incomplete array type.
5036  InitTy = IAT->getElementType();
5037  if (!S.isCompleteType(From->getBeginLoc(), InitTy))
5038  return Result;
5039 
5040  // Per DR1467:
5041  // If the parameter type is a class X and the initializer list has a single
5042  // element of type cv U, where U is X or a class derived from X, the
5043  // implicit conversion sequence is the one required to convert the element
5044  // to the parameter type.
5045  //
5046  // Otherwise, if the parameter type is a character array [... ]
5047  // and the initializer list has a single element that is an
5048  // appropriately-typed string literal (8.5.2 [dcl.init.string]), the
5049  // implicit conversion sequence is the identity conversion.
5050  if (From->getNumInits() == 1) {
5051  if (ToType->isRecordType()) {
5052  QualType InitType = From->getInit(0)->getType();
5053  if (S.Context.hasSameUnqualifiedType(InitType, ToType) ||
5054  S.IsDerivedFrom(From->getBeginLoc(), InitType, ToType))
5055  return TryCopyInitialization(S, From->getInit(0), ToType,
5056  SuppressUserConversions,
5057  InOverloadResolution,
5058  AllowObjCWritebackConversion);
5059  }
5060 
5061  if (AT && S.IsStringInit(From->getInit(0), AT)) {
5062  InitializedEntity Entity =
5063  InitializedEntity::InitializeParameter(S.Context, ToType,
5064  /*Consumed=*/false);
5065  if (S.CanPerformCopyInitialization(Entity, From)) {
5066  Result.setStandard();
5067  Result.Standard.setAsIdentityConversion();
5068  Result.Standard.setFromType(ToType);
5069  Result.Standard.setAllToTypes(ToType);
5070  return Result;
5071  }
5072  }
5073  }
5074 
5075  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p2: Otherwise, if the parameter type [...] (below).
5076  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p2:
5077  // If the parameter type is std::initializer_list<X> or "array of X" and
5078  // all the elements can be implicitly converted to X, the implicit
5079  // conversion sequence is the worst conversion necessary to convert an
5080  // element of the list to X.
5081  //
5082  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p3:
5083  // Otherwise, if the parameter type is "array of N X", if the initializer
5084  // list has exactly N elements or if it has fewer than N elements and X is
5085  // default-constructible, and if all the elements of the initializer list
5086  // can be implicitly converted to X, the implicit conversion sequence is
5087  // the worst conversion necessary to convert an element of the list to X.
5088  if (AT || S.isStdInitializerList(ToType, &InitTy)) {
5089  unsigned e = From->getNumInits();
5090  ImplicitConversionSequence DfltElt;
5091  DfltElt.setBad(BadConversionSequence::no_conversion, QualType(),
5092  QualType());
5093  QualType ContTy = ToType;
5094  bool IsUnbounded = false;
5095  if (AT) {
5096  InitTy = AT->getElementType();
5097  if (ConstantArrayType const *CT = dyn_cast<ConstantArrayType>(AT)) {
5098  if (CT->getSize().ult(e)) {
5099  // Too many inits, fatally bad
5100  Result.setBad(BadConversionSequence::too_many_initializers, From,
5101  ToType);
5102  Result.setInitializerListContainerType(ContTy, IsUnbounded);
5103  return Result;
5104  }
5105  if (CT->getSize().ugt(e)) {
5106  // Need an init from empty {}, is there one?
5107  InitListExpr EmptyList(S.Context, From->getEndLoc(), None,
5108  From->getEndLoc());
5109  EmptyList.setType(S.Context.VoidTy);
5110  DfltElt = TryListConversion(
5111  S, &EmptyList, InitTy, SuppressUserConversions,
5112  InOverloadResolution, AllowObjCWritebackConversion);
5113  if (DfltElt.isBad()) {
5114  // No {} init, fatally bad
5115  Result.setBad(BadConversionSequence::too_few_initializers, From,
5116  ToType);
5117  Result.setInitializerListContainerType(ContTy, IsUnbounded);
5118  return Result;
5119  }
5120  }
5121  } else {
5122  assert(isa<IncompleteArrayType>(AT) && "Expected incomplete array");
5123  IsUnbounded = true;
5124  if (!e) {
5125  // Cannot convert to zero-sized.
5126  Result.setBad(BadConversionSequence::too_few_initializers, From,
5127  ToType);
5128  Result.setInitializerListContainerType(ContTy, IsUnbounded);
5129  return Result;
5130  }
5131  llvm::APInt Size(S.Context.getTypeSize(S.Context.getSizeType()), e);
5132  ContTy = S.Context.getConstantArrayType(InitTy, Size, nullptr,
5133  ArrayType::Normal, 0);
5134  }
5135  }
5136 
5137  Result.setStandard();
5138  Result.Standard.setAsIdentityConversion();
5139  Result.Standard.setFromType(InitTy);
5140  Result.Standard.setAllToTypes(InitTy);
5141  for (unsigned i = 0; i < e; ++i) {
5142  Expr *Init = From->getInit(i);
5143  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS = TryCopyInitialization(
5144  S, Init, InitTy, SuppressUserConversions, InOverloadResolution,
5145  AllowObjCWritebackConversion);
5146 
5147  // Keep the worse conversion seen so far.
5148  // FIXME: Sequences are not totally ordered, so 'worse' can be
5149  // ambiguous. CWG has been informed.
5150  if (CompareImplicitConversionSequences(S, From->getBeginLoc(), ICS,
5151  Result) ==
5152  ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse) {
5153  Result = ICS;
5154  // Bail as soon as we find something unconvertible.
5155  if (Result.isBad()) {
5156  Result.setInitializerListContainerType(ContTy, IsUnbounded);
5157  return Result;
5158  }
5159  }
5160  }
5161 
5162  // If we needed any implicit {} initialization, compare that now.
5163  // over.ics.list/6 indicates we should compare that conversion. Again CWG
5164  // has been informed that this might not be the best thing.
5165  if (!DfltElt.isBad() && CompareImplicitConversionSequences(
5166  S, From->getEndLoc(), DfltElt, Result) ==
5167  ImplicitConversionSequence::Worse)
5168  Result = DfltElt;
5169  // Record the type being initialized so that we may compare sequences
5170  Result.setInitializerListContainerType(ContTy, IsUnbounded);
5171  return Result;
5172  }
5173 
5174  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p4:
5175  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p3:
5176  // Otherwise, if the parameter is a non-aggregate class X and overload
5177  // resolution chooses a single best constructor [...] the implicit
5178  // conversion sequence is a user-defined conversion sequence. If multiple
5179  // constructors are viable but none is better than the others, the
5180  // implicit conversion sequence is a user-defined conversion sequence.
5181  if (ToType->isRecordType() && !ToType->isAggregateType()) {
5182  // This function can deal with initializer lists.
5183  return TryUserDefinedConversion(S, From, ToType, SuppressUserConversions,
5184  AllowedExplicit::None,
5185  InOverloadResolution, /*CStyle=*/false,
5186  AllowObjCWritebackConversion,
5187  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/false);
5188  }
5189 
5190  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p5:
5191  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p4:
5192  // Otherwise, if the parameter has an aggregate type which can be
5193  // initialized from the initializer list [...] the implicit conversion
5194  // sequence is a user-defined conversion sequence.
5195  if (ToType->isAggregateType()) {
5196  // Type is an aggregate, argument is an init list. At this point it comes
5197  // down to checking whether the initialization works.
5198  // FIXME: Find out whether this parameter is consumed or not.
5199  InitializedEntity Entity =
5200  InitializedEntity::InitializeParameter(S.Context, ToType,
5201  /*Consumed=*/false);
5202  if (S.CanPerformAggregateInitializationForOverloadResolution(Entity,
5203  From)) {
5204  Result.setUserDefined();
5205  Result.UserDefined.Before.setAsIdentityConversion();
5206  // Initializer lists don't have a type.
5207  Result.UserDefined.Before.setFromType(QualType());
5208  Result.UserDefined.Before.setAllToTypes(QualType());
5209 
5210  Result.UserDefined.After.setAsIdentityConversion();
5211  Result.UserDefined.After.setFromType(ToType);
5212  Result.UserDefined.After.setAllToTypes(ToType);
5213  Result.UserDefined.ConversionFunction = nullptr;
5214  }
5215  return Result;
5216  }
5217 
5218  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p6:
5219  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p5:
5220  // Otherwise, if the parameter is a reference, see 13.3.3.1.4.
5221  if (ToType->isReferenceType()) {
5222  // The standard is notoriously unclear here, since 13.3.3.1.4 doesn't
5223  // mention initializer lists in any way. So we go by what list-
5224  // initialization would do and try to extrapolate from that.
5225 
5226  QualType T1 = ToType->castAs<ReferenceType>()->getPointeeType();
5227 
5228  // If the initializer list has a single element that is reference-related
5229  // to the parameter type, we initialize the reference from that.
5230  if (From->getNumInits() == 1) {
5231  Expr *Init = From->getInit(0);
5232 
5233  QualType T2 = Init->getType();
5234 
5235  // If the initializer is the address of an overloaded function, try
5236  // to resolve the overloaded function. If all goes well, T2 is the
5237  // type of the resulting function.
5238  if (S.Context.getCanonicalType(T2) == S.Context.OverloadTy) {
5239  DeclAccessPair Found;
5240  if (FunctionDecl *Fn = S.ResolveAddressOfOverloadedFunction(
5241  Init, ToType, false, Found))
5242  T2 = Fn->getType();
5243  }
5244 
5245  // Compute some basic properties of the types and the initializer.
5246  Sema::ReferenceCompareResult RefRelationship =
5247  S.CompareReferenceRelationship(From->getBeginLoc(), T1, T2);
5248 
5249  if (RefRelationship >= Sema::Ref_Related) {
5250  return TryReferenceInit(S, Init, ToType, /*FIXME*/ From->getBeginLoc(),
5251  SuppressUserConversions,
5252  /*AllowExplicit=*/false);
5253  }
5254  }
5255 
5256  // Otherwise, we bind the reference to a temporary created from the
5257  // initializer list.
5258  Result = TryListConversion(S, From, T1, SuppressUserConversions,
5259  InOverloadResolution,
5260  AllowObjCWritebackConversion);
5261  if (Result.isFailure())
5262  return Result;
5263  assert(!Result.isEllipsis() &&
5264  "Sub-initialization cannot result in ellipsis conversion.");
5265 
5266  // Can we even bind to a temporary?
5267  if (ToType->isRValueReferenceType() ||
5268  (T1.isConstQualified() && !T1.isVolatileQualified())) {
5269  StandardConversionSequence &SCS = Result.isStandard() ? Result.Standard :
5270  Result.UserDefined.After;
5271  SCS.ReferenceBinding = true;
5272  SCS.IsLvalueReference = ToType->isLValueReferenceType();
5273  SCS.BindsToRvalue = true;
5274  SCS.BindsToFunctionLvalue = false;
5275  SCS.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier = false;
5276  SCS.ObjCLifetimeConversionBinding = false;
5277  } else
5278  Result.setBad(BadConversionSequence::lvalue_ref_to_rvalue,
5279  From, ToType);
5280  return Result;
5281  }
5282 
5283  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p7:
5284  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p6:
5285  // Otherwise, if the parameter type is not a class:
5286  if (!ToType->isRecordType()) {
5287  // - if the initializer list has one element that is not itself an
5288  // initializer list, the implicit conversion sequence is the one
5289  // required to convert the element to the parameter type.
5290  unsigned NumInits = From->getNumInits();
5291  if (NumInits == 1 && !isa<InitListExpr>(From->getInit(0)))
5292  Result = TryCopyInitialization(S, From->getInit(0), ToType,
5293  SuppressUserConversions,
5294  InOverloadResolution,
5295  AllowObjCWritebackConversion);
5296  // - if the initializer list has no elements, the implicit conversion
5297  // sequence is the identity conversion.
5298  else if (NumInits == 0) {
5299  Result.setStandard();
5300  Result.Standard.setAsIdentityConversion();
5301  Result.Standard.setFromType(ToType);
5302  Result.Standard.setAllToTypes(ToType);
5303  }
5304  return Result;
5305  }
5306 
5307  // C++14 [over.ics.list]p8:
5308  // C++11 [over.ics.list]p7:
5309  // In all cases other than those enumerated above, no conversion is possible
5310  return Result;
5311 }
5312 
5313 /// TryCopyInitialization - Try to copy-initialize a value of type
5314 /// ToType from the expression From. Return the implicit conversion
5315 /// sequence required to pass this argument, which may be a bad
5316 /// conversion sequence (meaning that the argument cannot be passed to
5317 /// a parameter of this type). If @p SuppressUserConversions, then we
5318 /// do not permit any user-defined conversion sequences.
5319 static ImplicitConversionSequence
5320 TryCopyInitialization(Sema &S, Expr *From, QualType ToType,
5321  bool SuppressUserConversions,
5322  bool InOverloadResolution,
5323  bool AllowObjCWritebackConversion,
5324  bool AllowExplicit) {
5325  if (InitListExpr *FromInitList = dyn_cast<InitListExpr>(From))
5326  return TryListConversion(S, FromInitList, ToType, SuppressUserConversions,
5327  InOverloadResolution,AllowObjCWritebackConversion);
5328 
5329  if (ToType->isReferenceType())
5330  return TryReferenceInit(S, From, ToType,
5331  /*FIXME:*/ From->getBeginLoc(),
5332  SuppressUserConversions, AllowExplicit);
5333 
5334  return TryImplicitConversion(S, From, ToType,
5335  SuppressUserConversions,
5336  AllowedExplicit::None,
5337  InOverloadResolution,
5338  /*CStyle=*/false,
5339  AllowObjCWritebackConversion,
5340  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/false);
5341 }
5342 
5343 static bool TryCopyInitialization(const CanQualType FromQTy,
5344  const CanQualType ToQTy,
5345  Sema &S,
5346  SourceLocation Loc,
5347  ExprValueKind FromVK) {
5348  OpaqueValueExpr TmpExpr(Loc, FromQTy, FromVK);
5349  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS =
5350  TryCopyInitialization(S, &TmpExpr, ToQTy, true, true, false);
5351 
5352  return !ICS.isBad();
5353 }
5354 
5355 /// TryObjectArgumentInitialization - Try to initialize the object
5356 /// parameter of the given member function (@c Method) from the
5357 /// expression @p From.
5358 static ImplicitConversionSequence
5359 TryObjectArgumentInitialization(Sema &S, SourceLocation Loc, QualType FromType,
5360  Expr::Classification FromClassification,
5361  CXXMethodDecl *Method,
5362  CXXRecordDecl *ActingContext) {
5363  QualType ClassType = S.Context.getTypeDeclType(ActingContext);
5364  // [class.dtor]p2: A destructor can be invoked for a const, volatile or
5365  // const volatile object.
5366  Qualifiers Quals = Method->getMethodQualifiers();
5367  if (isa<CXXDestructorDecl>(Method)) {
5368  Quals.addConst();
5369  Quals.addVolatile();
5370  }
5371 
5372  QualType ImplicitParamType = S.Context.getQualifiedType(ClassType, Quals);
5373 
5374  // Set up the conversion sequence as a "bad" conversion, to allow us
5375  // to exit early.
5376  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS;
5377 
5378  // We need to have an object of class type.
5379  if (const PointerType *PT = FromType->getAs<PointerType>()) {
5380  FromType = PT->getPointeeType();
5381 
5382  // When we had a pointer, it's implicitly dereferenced, so we
5383  // better have an lvalue.
5384  assert(FromClassification.isLValue());
5385  }
5386 
5387  assert(FromType->isRecordType());
5388 
5389  // C++0x [over.match.funcs]p4:
5390  // For non-static member functions, the type of the implicit object
5391  // parameter is
5392  //
5393  // - "lvalue reference to cv X" for functions declared without a
5394  // ref-qualifier or with the & ref-qualifier
5395  // - "rvalue reference to cv X" for functions declared with the &&
5396  // ref-qualifier
5397  //
5398  // where X is the class of which the function is a member and cv is the
5399  // cv-qualification on the member function declaration.
5400  //
5401  // However, when finding an implicit conversion sequence for the argument, we
5402  // are not allowed to perform user-defined conversions
5403  // (C++ [over.match.funcs]p5). We perform a simplified version of
5404  // reference binding here, that allows class rvalues to bind to
5405  // non-constant references.
5406 
5407  // First check the qualifiers.
5408  QualType FromTypeCanon = S.Context.getCanonicalType(FromType);
5409  if (ImplicitParamType.getCVRQualifiers()
5410  != FromTypeCanon.getLocalCVRQualifiers() &&
5411  !ImplicitParamType.isAtLeastAsQualifiedAs(FromTypeCanon)) {
5412  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::bad_qualifiers,
5413  FromType, ImplicitParamType);
5414  return ICS;
5415  }
5416 
5417  if (FromTypeCanon.hasAddressSpace()) {
5418  Qualifiers QualsImplicitParamType = ImplicitParamType.getQualifiers();
5419  Qualifiers QualsFromType = FromTypeCanon.getQualifiers();
5420  if (!QualsImplicitParamType.isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(QualsFromType)) {
5421  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::bad_qualifiers,
5422  FromType, ImplicitParamType);
5423  return ICS;
5424  }
5425  }
5426 
5427  // Check that we have either the same type or a derived type. It
5428  // affects the conversion rank.
5429  QualType ClassTypeCanon = S.Context.getCanonicalType(ClassType);
5430  ImplicitConversionKind SecondKind;
5431  if (ClassTypeCanon == FromTypeCanon.getLocalUnqualifiedType()) {
5432  SecondKind = ICK_Identity;
5433  } else if (S.IsDerivedFrom(Loc, FromType, ClassType))
5434  SecondKind = ICK_Derived_To_Base;
5435  else {
5436  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::unrelated_class,
5437  FromType, ImplicitParamType);
5438  return ICS;
5439  }
5440 
5441  // Check the ref-qualifier.
5442  switch (Method->getRefQualifier()) {
5443  case RQ_None:
5444  // Do nothing; we don't care about lvalueness or rvalueness.
5445  break;
5446 
5447  case RQ_LValue:
5448  if (!FromClassification.isLValue() && !Quals.hasOnlyConst()) {
5449  // non-const lvalue reference cannot bind to an rvalue
5450  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::lvalue_ref_to_rvalue, FromType,
5451  ImplicitParamType);
5452  return ICS;
5453  }
5454  break;
5455 
5456  case RQ_RValue:
5457  if (!FromClassification.isRValue()) {
5458  // rvalue reference cannot bind to an lvalue
5459  ICS.setBad(BadConversionSequence::rvalue_ref_to_lvalue, FromType,
5460  ImplicitParamType);
5461  return ICS;
5462  }
5463  break;
5464  }
5465 
5466  // Success. Mark this as a reference binding.
5467  ICS.setStandard();
5468  ICS.Standard.setAsIdentityConversion();
5469  ICS.Standard.Second = SecondKind;
5470  ICS.Standard.setFromType(FromType);
5471  ICS.Standard.setAllToTypes(ImplicitParamType);
5472  ICS.Standard.ReferenceBinding = true;
5473  ICS.Standard.DirectBinding = true;
5474  ICS.Standard.IsLvalueReference = Method->getRefQualifier() != RQ_RValue;
5475  ICS.Standard.BindsToFunctionLvalue = false;
5476  ICS.Standard.BindsToRvalue = FromClassification.isRValue();
5477  ICS.Standard.BindsImplicitObjectArgumentWithoutRefQualifier
5478  = (Method->getRefQualifier() == RQ_None);
5479  return ICS;
5480 }
5481 
5482 /// PerformObjectArgumentInitialization - Perform initialization of
5483 /// the implicit object parameter for the given Method with the given
5484 /// expression.
5485 ExprResult
5486 Sema::PerformObjectArgumentInitialization(Expr *From,
5487  NestedNameSpecifier *Qualifier,
5488  NamedDecl *FoundDecl,
5489  CXXMethodDecl *Method) {
5490  QualType FromRecordType, DestType;
5491  QualType ImplicitParamRecordType =
5492  Method->getThisType()->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType();
5493 
5494  Expr::Classification FromClassification;
5495  if (const PointerType *PT = From->getType()->getAs<PointerType>()) {
5496  FromRecordType = PT->getPointeeType();
5497  DestType = Method->getThisType();
5498  FromClassification = Expr::Classification::makeSimpleLValue();
5499  } else {
5500  FromRecordType = From->getType();
5501  DestType = ImplicitParamRecordType;
5502  FromClassification = From->Classify(Context);
5503 
5504  // When performing member access on a prvalue, materialize a temporary.
5505  if (From->isPRValue()) {
5506  From = CreateMaterializeTemporaryExpr(FromRecordType, From,
5507  Method->getRefQualifier() !=
5508  RefQualifierKind::RQ_RValue);
5509  }
5510  }
5511 
5512  // Note that we always use the true parent context when performing
5513  // the actual argument initialization.
5514  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS = TryObjectArgumentInitialization(
5515  *this, From->getBeginLoc(), From->getType(), FromClassification, Method,
5516  Method->getParent());
5517  if (ICS.isBad()) {
5518  switch (ICS.Bad.Kind) {
5519  case BadConversionSequence::bad_qualifiers: {
5520  Qualifiers FromQs = FromRecordType.getQualifiers();
5521  Qualifiers ToQs = DestType.getQualifiers();
5522  unsigned CVR = FromQs.getCVRQualifiers() & ~ToQs.getCVRQualifiers();
5523  if (CVR) {
5524  Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_member_function_call_bad_cvr)
5525  << Method->getDeclName() << FromRecordType << (CVR - 1)
5526  << From->getSourceRange();
5527  Diag(Method->getLocation(), diag::note_previous_decl)
5528  << Method->getDeclName();
5529  return ExprError();
5530  }
5531  break;
5532  }
5533 
5534  case BadConversionSequence::lvalue_ref_to_rvalue:
5535  case BadConversionSequence::rvalue_ref_to_lvalue: {
5536  bool IsRValueQualified =
5537  Method->getRefQualifier() == RefQualifierKind::RQ_RValue;
5538  Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_member_function_call_bad_ref)
5539  << Method->getDeclName() << FromClassification.isRValue()
5540  << IsRValueQualified;
5541  Diag(Method->getLocation(), diag::note_previous_decl)
5542  << Method->getDeclName();
5543  return ExprError();
5544  }
5545 
5546  case BadConversionSequence::no_conversion:
5547  case BadConversionSequence::unrelated_class:
5548  break;
5549 
5550  case BadConversionSequence::too_few_initializers:
5551  case BadConversionSequence::too_many_initializers:
5552  llvm_unreachable("Lists are not objects");
5553  }
5554 
5555  return Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_member_function_call_bad_type)
5556  << ImplicitParamRecordType << FromRecordType
5557  << From->getSourceRange();
5558  }
5559 
5560  if (ICS.Standard.Second == ICK_Derived_To_Base) {
5561  ExprResult FromRes =
5562  PerformObjectMemberConversion(From, Qualifier, FoundDecl, Method);
5563  if (FromRes.isInvalid())
5564  return ExprError();
5565  From = FromRes.get();
5566  }
5567 
5568  if (!Context.hasSameType(From->getType(), DestType)) {
5569  CastKind CK;
5570  QualType PteeTy = DestType->getPointeeType();
5571  LangAS DestAS =
5572  PteeTy.isNull() ? DestType.getAddressSpace() : PteeTy.getAddressSpace();
5573  if (FromRecordType.getAddressSpace() != DestAS)
5574  CK = CK_AddressSpaceConversion;
5575  else
5576  CK = CK_NoOp;
5577  From = ImpCastExprToType(From, DestType, CK, From->getValueKind()).get();
5578  }
5579  return From;
5580 }
5581 
5582 /// TryContextuallyConvertToBool - Attempt to contextually convert the
5583 /// expression From to bool (C++0x [conv]p3).
5584 static ImplicitConversionSequence
5585 TryContextuallyConvertToBool(Sema &S, Expr *From) {
5586  // C++ [dcl.init]/17.8:
5587  // - Otherwise, if the initialization is direct-initialization, the source
5588  // type is std::nullptr_t, and the destination type is bool, the initial
5589  // value of the object being initialized is false.
5590  if (From->getType()->isNullPtrType())
5591  return ImplicitConversionSequence::getNullptrToBool(From->getType(),
5592  S.Context.BoolTy,
5593  From->isGLValue());
5594 
5595  // All other direct-initialization of bool is equivalent to an implicit
5596  // conversion to bool in which explicit conversions are permitted.
5597  return TryImplicitConversion(S, From, S.Context.BoolTy,
5598  /*SuppressUserConversions=*/false,
5599  AllowedExplicit::Conversions,
5600  /*InOverloadResolution=*/false,
5601  /*CStyle=*/false,
5602  /*AllowObjCWritebackConversion=*/false,
5603  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/false);
5604 }
5605 
5606 /// PerformContextuallyConvertToBool - Perform a contextual conversion
5607 /// of the expression From to bool (C++0x [conv]p3).
5608 ExprResult Sema::PerformContextuallyConvertToBool(Expr *From) {
5609  if (checkPlaceholderForOverload(*this, From))
5610  return ExprError();
5611 
5612  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS = TryContextuallyConvertToBool(*this, From);
5613  if (!ICS.isBad())
5614  return PerformImplicitConversion(From, Context.BoolTy, ICS, AA_Converting);
5615 
5616  if (!DiagnoseMultipleUserDefinedConversion(From, Context.BoolTy))
5617  return Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_typecheck_bool_condition)
5618  << From->getType() << From->getSourceRange();
5619  return ExprError();
5620 }
5621 
5622 /// Check that the specified conversion is permitted in a converted constant
5623 /// expression, according to C++11 [expr.const]p3. Return true if the conversion
5624 /// is acceptable.
5625 static bool CheckConvertedConstantConversions(Sema &S,
5626  StandardConversionSequence &SCS) {
5627  // Since we know that the target type is an integral or unscoped enumeration
5628  // type, most conversion kinds are impossible. All possible First and Third
5629  // conversions are fine.
5630  switch (SCS.Second) {
5631  case ICK_Identity:
5632  case ICK_Integral_Promotion:
5633  case ICK_Integral_Conversion: // Narrowing conversions are checked elsewhere.
5634  case ICK_Zero_Queue_Conversion:
5635  return true;
5636 
5637  case ICK_Boolean_Conversion:
5638  // Conversion from an integral or unscoped enumeration type to bool is
5639  // classified as ICK_Boolean_Conversion, but it's also arguably an integral
5640  // conversion, so we allow it in a converted constant expression.
5641  //
5642  // FIXME: Per core issue 1407, we should not allow this, but that breaks
5643  // a lot of popular code. We should at least add a warning for this
5644  // (non-conforming) extension.
5645  return SCS.getFromType()->isIntegralOrUnscopedEnumerationType() &&
5646  SCS.getToType(2)->isBooleanType();
5647 
5648  case ICK_Pointer_Conversion:
5649  case ICK_Pointer_Member:
5650  // C++1z: null pointer conversions and null member pointer conversions are
5651  // only permitted if the source type is std::nullptr_t.
5652  return SCS.getFromType()->isNullPtrType();
5653 
5654  case ICK_Floating_Promotion:
5655  case ICK_Complex_Promotion:
5656  case ICK_Floating_Conversion:
5657  case ICK_Complex_Conversion:
5658  case ICK_Floating_Integral:
5659  case ICK_Compatible_Conversion:
5660  case ICK_Derived_To_Base:
5661  case ICK_Vector_Conversion:
5662  case ICK_SVE_Vector_Conversion:
5663  case ICK_Vector_Splat:
5664  case ICK_Complex_Real:
5665  case ICK_Block_Pointer_Conversion:
5666  case ICK_TransparentUnionConversion:
5667  case ICK_Writeback_Conversion:
5668  case ICK_Zero_Event_Conversion:
5669  case ICK_C_Only_Conversion:
5670  case ICK_Incompatible_Pointer_Conversion:
5671  return false;
5672 
5673  case ICK_Lvalue_To_Rvalue:
5674  case ICK_Array_To_Pointer:
5675  case ICK_Function_To_Pointer:
5676  llvm_unreachable("found a first conversion kind in Second");
5677 
5678  case ICK_Function_Conversion:
5679  case ICK_Qualification:
5680  llvm_unreachable("found a third conversion kind in Second");
5681 
5682  case ICK_Num_Conversion_Kinds:
5683  break;
5684  }
5685 
5686  llvm_unreachable("unknown conversion kind");
5687 }
5688 
5689 /// CheckConvertedConstantExpression - Check that the expression From is a
5690 /// converted constant expression of type T, perform the conversion and produce
5691 /// the converted expression, per C++11 [expr.const]p3.
5692 static ExprResult CheckConvertedConstantExpression(Sema &S, Expr *From,
5693  QualType T, APValue &Value,
5694  Sema::CCEKind CCE,
5695  bool RequireInt,
5696  NamedDecl *Dest) {
5697  assert(S.getLangOpts().CPlusPlus11 &&
5698  "converted constant expression outside C++11");
5699 
5700  if (checkPlaceholderForOverload(S, From))
5701  return ExprError();
5702 
5703  // C++1z [expr.const]p3:
5704  // A converted constant expression of type T is an expression,
5705  // implicitly converted to type T, where the converted
5706  // expression is a constant expression and the implicit conversion
5707  // sequence contains only [... list of conversions ...].
5708  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS =
5709  (CCE == Sema::CCEK_ExplicitBool || CCE == Sema::CCEK_Noexcept)
5710  ? TryContextuallyConvertToBool(S, From)
5711  : TryCopyInitialization(S, From, T,
5712  /*SuppressUserConversions=*/false,
5713  /*InOverloadResolution=*/false,
5714  /*AllowObjCWritebackConversion=*/false,
5715  /*AllowExplicit=*/false);
5716  StandardConversionSequence *SCS = nullptr;
5717  switch (ICS.getKind()) {
5718  case ImplicitConversionSequence::StandardConversion:
5719  SCS = &ICS.Standard;
5720  break;
5721  case ImplicitConversionSequence::UserDefinedConversion:
5722  if (T->isRecordType())
5723  SCS = &ICS.UserDefined.Before;
5724  else
5725  SCS = &ICS.UserDefined.After;
5726  break;
5727  case ImplicitConversionSequence::AmbiguousConversion:
5728  case ImplicitConversionSequence::BadConversion:
5729  if (!S.DiagnoseMultipleUserDefinedConversion(From, T))
5730  return S.Diag(From->getBeginLoc(),
5731  diag::err_typecheck_converted_constant_expression)
5732  << From->getType() << From->getSourceRange() << T;
5733  return ExprError();
5734 
5735  case ImplicitConversionSequence::EllipsisConversion:
5736  llvm_unreachable("ellipsis conversion in converted constant expression");
5737  }
5738 
5739  // Check that we would only use permitted conversions.
5740  if (!CheckConvertedConstantConversions(S, *SCS)) {
5741  return S.Diag(From->getBeginLoc(),
5742  diag::err_typecheck_converted_constant_expression_disallowed)
5743  << From->getType() << From->getSourceRange() << T;
5744  }
5745  // [...] and where the reference binding (if any) binds directly.
5746  if (SCS->ReferenceBinding && !SCS->DirectBinding) {
5747  return S.Diag(From->getBeginLoc(),
5748  diag::err_typecheck_converted_constant_expression_indirect)
5749  << From->getType() << From->getSourceRange() << T;
5750  }
5751 
5752  // Usually we can simply apply the ImplicitConversionSequence we formed
5753  // earlier, but that's not guaranteed to work when initializing an object of
5754  // class type.
5755  ExprResult Result;
5756  if (T->isRecordType()) {
5757  assert(CCE == Sema::CCEK_TemplateArg &&
5758  "unexpected class type converted constant expr");
5759  Result = S.PerformCopyInitialization(
5760  InitializedEntity::InitializeTemplateParameter(
5761  T, cast<NonTypeTemplateParmDecl>(Dest)),
5762  SourceLocation(), From);
5763  } else {
5764  Result = S.PerformImplicitConversion(From, T, ICS, Sema::AA_Converting);
5765  }
5766  if (Result.isInvalid())
5767  return Result;
5768 
5769  // C++2a [intro.execution]p5:
5770  // A full-expression is [...] a constant-expression [...]
5771  Result =
5772  S.ActOnFinishFullExpr(Result.get(), From->getExprLoc(),
5773  /*DiscardedValue=*/false, /*IsConstexpr=*/true);
5774  if (Result.isInvalid())
5775  return Result;
5776 
5777  // Check for a narrowing implicit conversion.
5778  bool ReturnPreNarrowingValue = false;
5779  APValue PreNarrowingValue;
5780  QualType PreNarrowingType;
5781  switch (SCS->getNarrowingKind(S.Context, Result.get(), PreNarrowingValue,
5782  PreNarrowingType)) {
5783  case NK_Dependent_Narrowing:
5784  // Implicit conversion to a narrower type, but the expression is
5785  // value-dependent so we can't tell whether it's actually narrowing.
5786  case NK_Variable_Narrowing:
5787  // Implicit conversion to a narrower type, and the value is not a constant
5788  // expression. We'll diagnose this in a moment.
5789  case NK_Not_Narrowing:
5790  break;
5791 
5792  case NK_Constant_Narrowing:
5793  if (CCE == Sema::CCEK_ArrayBound &&
5794  PreNarrowingType->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() &&
5795  PreNarrowingValue.isInt()) {
5796  // Don't diagnose array bound narrowing here; we produce more precise
5797  // errors by allowing the un-narrowed value through.
5798  ReturnPreNarrowingValue = true;
5799  break;
5800  }
5801  S.Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::ext_cce_narrowing)
5802  << CCE << /*Constant*/ 1
5803  << PreNarrowingValue.getAsString(S.Context, PreNarrowingType) << T;
5804  break;
5805 
5806  case NK_Type_Narrowing:
5807  // FIXME: It would be better to diagnose that the expression is not a
5808  // constant expression.
5809  S.Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::ext_cce_narrowing)
5810  << CCE << /*Constant*/ 0 << From->getType() << T;
5811  break;
5812  }
5813 
5814  if (Result.get()->isValueDependent()) {
5815  Value = APValue();
5816  return Result;
5817  }
5818 
5819  // Check the expression is a constant expression.
5820  SmallVector<PartialDiagnosticAt, 8> Notes;
5821  Expr::EvalResult Eval;
5822  Eval.Diag = &Notes;
5823 
5824  ConstantExprKind Kind;
5825  if (CCE == Sema::CCEK_TemplateArg && T->isRecordType())
5826  Kind = ConstantExprKind::ClassTemplateArgument;
5827  else if (CCE == Sema::CCEK_TemplateArg)
5828  Kind = ConstantExprKind::NonClassTemplateArgument;
5829  else
5830  Kind = ConstantExprKind::Normal;
5831 
5832  if (!Result.get()->EvaluateAsConstantExpr(Eval, S.Context, Kind) ||
5833  (RequireInt && !Eval.Val.isInt())) {
5834  // The expression can't be folded, so we can't keep it at this position in
5835  // the AST.
5836  Result = ExprError();
5837  } else {
5838  Value = Eval.Val;
5839 
5840  if (Notes.empty()) {
5841  // It's a constant expression.
5842  Expr *E = ConstantExpr::Create(S.Context, Result.get(), Value);
5843  if (ReturnPreNarrowingValue)
5844  Value = std::move(PreNarrowingValue);
5845  return E;
5846  }
5847  }
5848 
5849  // It's not a constant expression. Produce an appropriate diagnostic.
5850  if (Notes.size() == 1 &&
5851  Notes[0].second.getDiagID() == diag::note_invalid_subexpr_in_const_expr) {
5852  S.Diag(Notes[0].first, diag::err_expr_not_cce) << CCE;
5853  } else if (!Notes.empty() && Notes[0].second.getDiagID() ==
5854  diag::note_constexpr_invalid_template_arg) {
5855  Notes[0].second.setDiagID(diag::err_constexpr_invalid_template_arg);
5856  for (unsigned I = 0; I < Notes.size(); ++I)
5857  S.Diag(Notes[I].first, Notes[I].second);
5858  } else {
5859  S.Diag(From->getBeginLoc(), diag::err_expr_not_cce)
5860  << CCE << From->getSourceRange();
5861  for (unsigned I = 0; I < Notes.size(); ++I)
5862  S.Diag(Notes[I].first, Notes[I].second);
5863  }
5864  return ExprError();
5865 }
5866 
5867 ExprResult Sema::CheckConvertedConstantExpression(Expr *From, QualType T,
5868  APValue &Value, CCEKind CCE,
5869  NamedDecl *Dest) {
5870  return ::CheckConvertedConstantExpression(*this, From, T, Value, CCE, false,
5871  Dest);
5872 }
5873 
5874 ExprResult Sema::CheckConvertedConstantExpression(Expr *From, QualType T,
5875  llvm::APSInt &Value,
5876  CCEKind CCE) {
5877  assert(T->isIntegralOrEnumerationType() && "unexpected converted const type");
5878 
5879  APValue V;
5880  auto R = ::CheckConvertedConstantExpression(*this, From, T, V, CCE, true,
5881  /*Dest=*/nullptr);
5882  if (!R.isInvalid() && !R.get()->isValueDependent())
5883  Value = V.getInt();
5884  return R;
5885 }

5887 
5888 /// dropPointerConversions - If the given standard conversion sequence
5889 /// involves any pointer conversions, remove them. This may change
5890 /// the result type of the conversion sequence.
5891 static void dropPointerConversion(StandardConversionSequence &SCS) {
5892  if (SCS.Second == ICK_Pointer_Conversion) {
5893  SCS.Second = ICK_Identity;
5894  SCS.Third = ICK_Identity;
5895  SCS.ToTypePtrs[2] = SCS.ToTypePtrs[1] = SCS.ToTypePtrs[0];
5896  }
5897 }
5898 
5899 /// TryContextuallyConvertToObjCPointer - Attempt to contextually
5900 /// convert the expression From to an Objective-C pointer type.
5901 static ImplicitConversionSequence
5902 TryContextuallyConvertToObjCPointer(Sema &S, Expr *From) {
5903  // Do an implicit conversion to 'id'.
5904  QualType Ty = S.Context.getObjCIdType();
5905  ImplicitConversionSequence ICS
5906  = TryImplicitConversion(S, From, Ty,
5907  // FIXME: Are these flags correct?
5908  /*SuppressUserConversions=*/false,
5909  AllowedExplicit::Conversions,
5910  /*InOverloadResolution=*/false,
5911  /*CStyle=*/false,
5912  /*AllowObjCWritebackConversion=*/false,
5913  /*AllowObjCConversionOnExplicit=*/true);
5914 
5915  // Strip off any final conversions to 'id'.
5916  switch (ICS.getKind()) {
5917  case ImplicitConversionSequence::BadConversion:
5918  case ImplicitConversionSequence::AmbiguousConversion:
5919  case ImplicitConversionSequence::EllipsisConversion:
5920  break;
5921 
5922  case ImplicitConversionSequence::UserDefinedConversion:
5923  dropPointerConversion(ICS.UserDefined.After);
5924  break;
5925 
5926  case ImplicitConversionSequence::StandardConversion:
5927  dropPointerConversion(ICS.Standard);
5928  break;
5929  }
5930 
5931  return ICS;
5932 }
5933 
5934 /// PerformContextuallyConvertToObjCPointer - Perform a contextual
5935 /// conversion of the expression From to an Objective-C pointer type.
5936 /// Returns a valid but null ExprResult if no conversion sequence exists.
5937 ExprResult Sema::PerformContextuallyConvertToObjCPointer(Expr *From) {
